# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: automobile-engine-replacement
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The **Chrysler Hemi engine**, known by the trademark **Hemi** or **HEMI**, is a series of high-performance American overhead valve V8 engines built by Chrysler with hemispherical combustion chambers.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Three generations have been produced: the FirePower series (with displacements from 241 to 392 cu in (3.9 to 6.4 L) from 1951 until 1958; a 426 cu in (7.0 L) race and street engine from 1964 through 1971; and family of advanced Hemis (displacing between 5.7 and 6.4 L (348 and 391 cu in) since 2003.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Although Chrysler is most identified with "Hemi" as a marketing term, many other auto manufacturers have incorporated Hemispherical cylinder head designs.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] During the 1970s and 1980s, Chrysler also applied the term *Hemi* to their Australian-made Hemi-6 Engine, and a 4-cylinder Mitsubishi 2.6 L engine installed in various North American market vehicles.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The main advantage of a hemispherical head engine over other head designs is power.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] On the other hand, hemi head engines tend to have complex valve trains, are expensive to build, and are larger and heavier than conventional designs.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] A hemispherical combustion chamber is efficient, with an excellent surface-to-volume ratio, minimal heat loss to the cylinder head, and room for two large valves.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] However, it allows no more than two valves per cylinder because of their large size, and they are necessarily heavier than those in a multi-valve engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The intake and exhaust valves lie on opposite sides of the chamber and necessitate a "cross-flow" head design.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Because the combustion chamber is a partial hemisphere, a flat-topped piston would yield a low compression ratio unless a very long stroke is used.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The piston crown is domed to protrude into the head at top dead center to attain the desired compression ratio.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The result is a combustion chamber in the shape of the space between where the domed piston stops and the dome shape in the head receiving it.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The hemi-head design places the spark plug at or near the chamber's center to promote a strong flame front.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] However, if the hemi-head hemisphere is of equal diameter to the piston, there is minimal squish for proper turbulence to mix fuel and air thoroughly.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Thus, hemi-heads, because of their lack of squish, are more sensitive to fuel octane rating; a given compression ratio will require a higher octane rating to avoid detonation in a hemi engine than in some conventional engine designs, such as the wedge and bathtub.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The hemi head always has intake and exhaust valve stems that point in different directions, requiring a large, wide cylinder head and complex rocker arm geometry in both cam-in-block and single overhead cam engines (dual overhead cam engines may not have rocker arms).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] This adds to the overall width of the engine, limiting the vehicles in which it can be installed.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Significant challenges in the commercialization of engine designs using hemispherical chambers revolved around the valve actuation, specifically how to make it effective, efficient, and reliable at an acceptable cost.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] This complexity was referenced early in Chrysler's development of their 1950s hemi engine: the head was referred to in company advertising as the *Double Rocker Shaft* head.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Chrysler developed its first experimental hemi engine for the Republic P-47 Thunderbolt fighter aircraft.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The XIV-2220 was an inverted overhead-valve (OHV) V16 rated at 2,500 hp (1,860 kW).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The P-47 was already in production with a Pratt & Whitney radial engine when the XIV-2220 flew successfully in trials in 1945 as a possible upgrade, but the war was winding down and it did not go into production.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] However, the exercise gave Chrysler engineers valuable research and development experience with two-valve hemi combustion chamber dynamics and parameters.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] In addition to the aircraft engine, Chrysler and Continental Motors Company worked together to develop the air-cooled AV-1790-5B V12 Hemi engine used in the M47 Patton tank.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Chrysler applied their military experience with the hemispherical combustion chamber to its first automobile engine, an OHV V8 engine released under the name **FirePower**, not "Hemi," in 1950 for the 1951 model year.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The first version of the FirePower engine had a displacement of 331 cu in (5.4 L) and produced 180 bhp (134 kW).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Eventually, three of the four Chrysler divisions had their own version of the FirePower engine, with different displacements and designations, and having almost no parts in common.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] This lack of commonality was due in part to the three engine versions using different bore spacings (the center-to-center distance between adjacent cylinders).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Chrysler and Imperial called their versions the *FirePower*.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Dodge had a smaller version, known as the *Red Ram*.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Only Plymouth did not have a version, but retained the Dodge poly-head engines.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] There was no Plymouth Hemi engine until the 1964 426.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Briggs Cunningham used the Chrysler version in some of his race cars for international motorsports.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] A Chrysler-powered Cunningham C-5R won its class in 1953.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Cunningham switched away from these designs in 1959 when Chrysler temporarily abandoned the hemispherical concept in favor of the wedge-head B engine until 1964.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Carl Kiekhaefer also used the Chrysler engines in his NASCAR cars from 1955 and 1956, winning the Grand National Series championship both years.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Collectively, the 1951–1958 Hemi engines are now commonly retroactively referred to as first-generation Hemi engines, which can be identified by the rear-mounted distributor and the spark plugs in a row down the center of wide valve covers.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] There were plans in 1951 for a Plymouth dual overhead cam Hemi V6 displacing 235 cubic inches (3.9 L) designed by Chrysler's Powerplant Research and Engine Design division.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Known internally as **A173**, it was meant to be a powerful, fuel-efficient alternative to Ford's V8 and to replace Plymouth's venerable flathead six.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] However, the plans were scrapped because of high build costs and the then-unusual design.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] All Chrysler FirePower engines are oversquare; i.e. their bore is larger than their stroke.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] This first FirePower engine, used from 1951 to 1955, has a bore of 3.8125 in (96.8 mm) and a stroke of 3.625 in (92.1 mm) for a piston displacement of 331.1 cu in (5,425 cc), with a deck height of 10.385 in (263.8 mm) ("low deck").
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The bore spacing, shared by all Chrysler FirePower engines, was 4.5625 in (115.9 mm), the largest of any first generation Hemi engines.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Most used a two-barrel carburetor and produced 180 bhp (134 kW), with the exception of the 1955 Chrysler C-300 equipped with dual Carter WCFB four-barrel carburetors and was rated at 300 hp (224 kW).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The 300B engine was rated at 340 bhp (254 kW), while the New Yorker and Imperial 354 engine configuration produced 280 bhp (209 kW).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] For the 300B, an optional 355 hp (265 kW; 360 PS) version was available, making it the first American V8 to be rated at one horsepower per cubic inch.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] (Note that before 1972, horsepower was SAE gross (equivalent to maximum output); thereafter, it was rated as SAE net (power delivered to the transmission, less accessories, emission controls, exhaust system, and other power-sinks).) The 354 was also modified.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The Hemi was optimized for heavy-duty truck service.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] These were available with one or two four-barrel carburetors, and were offered in Dodge's heaviest-duty models as the 'Power Giant V-8' from 1957 through 1959; they were the largest of four Hemi truck engines offered by Dodge in the 1950s.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The 354 was also offered in certain models with polyspheric heads rather than hemi heads.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The combustion chambers on these had similarities to both hemi and wedge heads, but were closer in weight to wedge heads.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Thus, both 354 poly and 354 Hemi V8 engines were variously available in 1957.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The actual displacement is 392.67 cu in (6,435 cc).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The deck height, at 10.87 in (276.1 mm), was 1⁄2 in (13 mm) taller than that of the previous blocks.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Because its deck was taller, the heads were cast with wider intake ports so that earlier manifolds could be used with the new heads on the new taller block.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] For 1958, Chrysler offered the 392 in two configurations: 325 bhp (242 kW) with 9.25:1 compression and 345 bhp (257 kW) with 10:1 compression, both with a single four-barrel carburetor.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] A dual four-barrel version of the 392 available in the 1957–58 Chrysler 300C and 300D cars was rated at 375 bhp (280 kW); the 300D, and some marine and industrial engines, used a (now rare) adjustable rocker.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] An extremely rare option available on the 1958 300D was Bendix "Electrojector" fuel injection, with which the 392 was rated at 390 bhp (291 kW).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Due to reliability problems with the primitive onboard computer which controlled the injection system; however, 15 of the 16 300D cars built with the fuel injection option were recalled and retrofitted with carburetors.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] In the late 1950s and early 1960s, drag racers found the 392 to be a formidable engine and continued to run them competitively into the 1970s.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] DeSoto's Hemi engines were called FireDome and served as the naming convention for the DeSoto Firedome sedan.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] In 1952, DeSoto introduced its version of the FirePower (FireDome), with a bore of 3.625 in (92.08 mm) and stroke of 3.344 in (84.94 mm), for a displacement of 276.1 cu in (4.5 L).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The bore spacing, shared by all DeSoto FirePower engines, was 4.3125 in (109.54 mm).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] It was a hot seller, with 50,000 vehicles using the engine until it was replaced in 1954.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] In 1955, DeSoto increased the displacement of the FirePower (FireDome), by increasing the bore to 3.72 in (94.49 mm) for a displacement of 291 cu in (4.8 L).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Power output was 185 bhp (138 kW) with a 2-barrel carburetor for the Firedome models and 200 bhp (149 kW) with a 4-barrel carburetor for the Fireflite models.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] For 1956, the displacement for the Firedome and Fireflite models was increased again to 330 cu in (5.4 L) by increasing the stroke to 3.80 in (96.52 mm).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Power output was 230 bhp (172 kW) with a 2-barrel carburetor for the Firedome models and 255 bhp (190 kW) with a 4-barrel carburetor for the Fireflite models.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Displacement was increased again for the 1956 (DeSoto Adventurer only) and 1957 (Firedome and Fireflite models) to 341.1 cu in (5.6 L).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Bore was increased to 3.78 in (96.0 mm), but stroke remained at 3.80 in (96.5 mm).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The DeSoto Adventurer had a compression ratio of 9.5:1, using a special camshaft profile for hydraulic lifters, and produced 320 bhp (239 kW) using dual Carter WCFB four-barrel carburetors.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The 1956 Adventurer was the premiere named high-performance version—the DeSoto equivalent of the twin four-barrel Chrysler 300.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The largest DeSoto engine for 1957 was the DeSoto Adventurer offering 344.6 cu in (5.6 L) with square bore and stroke dimensions of 3.80 inches.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The DeSoto Adventurer used dual Carter WCFB four-barrel carburetors for a rating of 345 bhp (257 kW), producing one horsepower per cubic inch (the first American car to do so as standard equipment) using a similar intake manifold to the 1956 341 Adventurer and a similar camshaft.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The compression ratio remained at 9.5:1.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Dodge's Hemi was introduced in 1953 as the Red Ram.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Dodge did not have a V8 engine until one was developed specifically for the line in 1953 based on the 1951 Chrysler hemi design, but downsized for these smaller cars.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] They have the smallest bore center spacing of any hemi engine at 4.1875 in (106.4 mm).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] They do not share any major dimensions or components with the larger Chrysler and DeSoto hemi engines, or the Plymouth A engines.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] From 1955 to 1958 (see 1956 D500 Dodge D-500 cars and packages: early performance cars) lower-performance Hemi-based alternatives to the Dodge hemi were introduced by substituting less complex poly (single rocker shaft) heads and valve train parts, including one variant only built as a poly (259").
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] These were used in low-line 1955-58 DeSotos and Dodges, and 1955-56 high-line Plymouths.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Dodge introduced the 241.3 cu in (4.0 L) engine in 1953.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] With a low compression ratio of 7.0:1 (in 1953 and for the 1954 Meadowbrook), the 241 produced 140 bhp (104 kW).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] For 1954, the more senior Dodges received a higher 7.5:1 compression ratio 150 bhp (112 kW) version.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] This engine is not the same as the Plymouth 241, which had polyspheric heads.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The 241 Dodge Hemi only lasted two years, being replaced by the 270 for 1955.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The D553 1955/1956 Dodge Red Ram Hemi 270 displaced 270 cu in (4.4 L) and was used in premium 1955 and 1956 Dodge vehicles.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] It was not the same as the 270 poly-head.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] In the Dodge Coronet, the 270 produced 183 bhp (136 kW) at a compression ratio of 7.6:1.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] In higher trims like the Dodge Royal, the "Super Red Ram" featured a four-barrel carburetor and produced 193 bhp (144 kW) at the same compression ratio.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] For 1956, Dodge increased the displacement to 315 cu in (5.2 L) with a longer 3.80 in (96.5 mm) stroke and a taller raised-deck block, but used polyspheric rather than hemi heads on the base version.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The optional high-performance **D-500** version had a four-barrel carburetor and a larger-valved Dodge hemispherical combustion chambered head.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Also, a "race only" package called the D-500-1 or DASH 1 was available with a special aluminum dual four-barrel intake that sported a pair of Carter WCFB carburetors similar to the ones on the Chrysler 300B and DeSoto Adventurer.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] This engine used the same cylinder heads as the base D-500 model.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] In 1957 the D-501 was the Chrysler 354 engine, not a Dodge-based engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Dodge released the 325 cu in (5.3 L) "Super Red Ram" engine for 1957.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] It used a 3+11⁄16 in (93.7 mm; 3.69 in) bore and 3.80 in (96.5 mm) stroke, and a polyspheric chambered head (referenced as 'KDS') in its base version.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] A higher performance 325 was offered with hemi heads as the 'KD-500'.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The 'KD-500-1' came with dual four-barrel carburetors.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Even though the hemi headed offerings sported "dimples" in the valve covers for mechanical adjuster clearance, all engines had hydraulic lifters.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] “In December 1962 a request was made of engineering staff to develop an engine and vehicle combination capable of winning stock car competitive closed circuit track events throughout the country.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] It was further requested that a version of the engine suitable for use in supervised timed vehicle acceleration drag events also be made part of the engine portion of this program.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Both of these applications were to share the same basic design and development; thus a decision on the basic engine itself was one that required careful consideration.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] However, the decision for Chrysler was obvious.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The hemi engine had been a production engine from 1950 until it was discontinued in 1958.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The background of development that preceded the production version of the engine was available, as was experience in converting the engine for competition use.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Chrysler hemi engines had been used previously in track events, and were still in use in many drag events….The design of the new hemi engine began in January 1963 with the Feb.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] 23, 1964 Daytona Beach, Fla. race set as the first target date.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] A number of engine design avenues were initially explored in order to gain as many performance and durability features as possible while still retaining much of the existing [production] cylinder block tooling as practical.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The final design selected was deemed to have the potential necessary to win and the program was launched.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The engine requirements were to include a single 4 barrel carbuetor 426 cu in. track engine, and single barrel carburetor 396 cu in. track engine and a two 4 barrel carburetor 426 cu in. drag engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Immediately following the initial introduction of the engine, a production run of several hundred drag engines and cars were planned to be built.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The article continued: "Experimental procurement of the 426 cu in. hemi engine was started in July 1963 and was completed by the end of November.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The first engine ran under its own power on Dec.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] This engine was built as a track engine; the drag engine version was built later the same month.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The 396 cu in. track engine had subsequently been removed from the rules and the engine was never built.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] This 426 cu in. track engine was used extensively throughout the 1964 season.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The production of several hundred drag engines was completed by the end of the 1964 model year.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] A detuned high volume street version of the 426 hemi was designed, developed, released, and tooled as part of the 1966 model offering…With this release, full eligibility of the engine for 1966 track use was again established.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The 1960s 426 was the first engine called "Hemi" by Chrysler, the 426 was nicknamed the "elephant engine" at the time, a reference to its high power, heavy weight, and large physical dimensions.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Its 10.72 in (272.3 mm) deck height and 4.80 in (121.9 mm) bore spacing made it the biggest engine in racing at the time.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The 426 Hemi "Track" version, produced for use in NASCAR, was raced in a Plymouth Belvedere in 1964 by drivers such as Richard Petty.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] It was not initially available to the general public.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Complaints by Ford regarding its power led to the "Race Hemi" being banned from NASCAR's 1965 season due to its unavailability in production vehicles.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] However, several special homologated production versions of the Dodge Dart, the Plymouth Fury, and later, in 1965, the Dodge Coronet, were produced with aluminum fenders and bumpers for drag racing and made available to the general public.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Chrysler introduced the "Street Hemi" in 1966 for its intermediate range of cars and sold the required number of Hemi engines to the public to homologate its use for stock car racing in NASCAR events in 1966.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The “Street” engine featured a heated intake manifold, cast iron exhaust manifolds, automatic choke, and a milder cam.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The "Street Hemi" version was rated at 425 bhp (431 PS; 317 kW) at 5000 rpm SAE gross and 490 lb⋅ft (664 N⋅m) at 4000 rpm of torque.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] In actual dynamometer testing, it produced 433.5 hp (323 kW; 440 PS) and 472 lb⋅ft (640 N⋅m) of torque in purely stock form.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Chrysler's sales literature published both the gross 425 hp (317 kW; 431 PS) and net 350 hp (261 kW; 355 PS) ratings for 1971.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The “Track” and “Drag” engines were more alike than the “Street” engine was with either.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Among differening specifications in these racing engines for 1964-66 were: piston weights, intake valve diameter, water pumps, carburetion, camshaft profiles, and construction material (more aluminum and magnesium in “Drag” engine).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] There were many differences between the Hemi and the 426 Wedge, including the Hemi having cross-bolted steel main bearing caps and a different head bolt pattern.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Although all manufacturers were familiar with multi-valve engines and hemispherical combustion chambers, adding more valves per cylinder and designing the complex valvetrain they require were expensive ways of improving the high–revolutions per minute (rpm) breathing of production vehicles.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] By canting the angle of the NASCAR-mandated two valves per cylinder, significantly larger valves could be used.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Both the Chrysler 426 Hemi and all Chrysler RB engines were oversquare, with the 426 Hemi and 426 Wedge sharing a 4+1⁄4 in × 3+3⁄4 in (108.0 mm × 95.3 mm) bore and stroke.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Blocks for the 426 Hemi were stress relieved at the factory, to prevent cracking under high RPM loads.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] It was a family of engines covering everything from street engines to light weight competition engines.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] While the basic design was a hemispherical head with a center spark plug, the parameters varied greatly, depending on the intended use of the engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Differences between the racing Hemis and the street version, including but not limited to compression ratio, camshaft, intake manifold, exhaust manifold.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Some 1960s NASCAR and NHRA Hemi engines featured magnesium cross-ram intake manifolds and magnesium oil pans in an attempt to reduce the massive weight of the overall engine, along with chain-driven internal dry sump oil systems.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The main differences were in airflow and endurance to repeated high stress testing.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The Street Hemis were designed to be long lasting with high idle capabilities, while the A-864 and A-990 heads, designed for use on the race track, were designed for maximum volumetric efficiency at high engine speeds.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Almost every modern street and racing engine that is known as a Hemi has switched to using an aluminum engine block.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Using the high grade 356-T6 aluminum aftermarket blocks and heads have improved the cooling of the engine significantly, and has reduced the weight of the iron components by over 100lbs.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Modern engine design using these new material components is utilizing forged aluminum pistons to deal with the additional heat of the higher RPM’s and load.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The current-production "HEMI" engine heads are flatter and more complex than the 1950s–'70s Hemi V8 chamber.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The combustion chambers are no longer truly hemispherical.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] It uses a coil-on-plug (distributor-less) ignition system and two spark plugs per cylinder to shorten flame travel leading to more consistent combustion and reduced emissions.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Like most of Chrysler's past-model Hemi-head engines, the 5.7 L version is rated at approximately one horsepower per cubic inch (the current engines are SAE net, whereas the old Hemi engines were rated SAE gross).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] It also achieved 4% better fuel economy.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Variable valve timing (VVT) was also introduced.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] A new variable displacement technology called Multi-Displacement System (MDS) is used in some versions which can shut off two cylinders on each bank under light load to improve fuel economy.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The 5.7 L HEMI was released for model year 2003 on the Dodge Ram pickup trucks to supplant the Magnum 5.9 engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] From 2004 to 2013, it was the only available gasoline engine in the Ram Heavy Duty.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Chrysler later made the 5.7 L Hemi available in all models of the 2004 Dodge Ram, Dodge Durango, the 2005 Chrysler 300C, Dodge Magnum R/T, Jeep Grand Cherokee, the 2006 Dodge Charger R/T, Jeep Commander, the 2007 Chrysler Aspen, the 2009 Dodge Challenger R/T, and the 2022 Jeep Wagoneer.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] For manual transmission applications (Challenger and 3/4- and 1-ton Ram pickups), cylinder deactivation is not included.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The 5.7 L (345 cu in) Hemi in the Ram delivered 345 hp (257 kW) and 375 lb⋅ft (508 N⋅m), but 340 hp (254 kW) and 390 lb⋅ft (529 N⋅m) for the 300C and Magnum R/T, which is exactly 100 hp (75 kW) more than the old 5.9 engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] It is a 90-degree V8, 2-valve pushrod design like the past Magnum series engines, displacing 5,654 cc (345 cu in), with a bore of 3.917 in (99.49 mm) and a stroke of 3.578 in (90.88 mm).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The 5.7 L Hemi is made at Chrysler's Saltillo Engine plant in Ramos Arizpe, Mexico.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The Hemi was on the Ward's 10 Best Engines list for 2003 through 2007, and again in 2009.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Chrysler made various revisions to the 5.7 L for the 2009 model year.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The first for all applications was what Chrysler called Variable Camshaft Timing or VCT.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] VCT (which is essentially variable valve timing) uses an oil control valve that controls oil flow to a unique camshaft sprocket that contains a phasing device, which depending on the operation of the oil control valve, either advances or retards camshaft timing.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Cylinder heads were revised to increase flow.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Though the intake manifold was also changed on all applications, it was still model-specific.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The Dodge Ram, non-Hybrid Electric Vehicle (HEV) Chrysler Aspens, and non-HEV Dodge Durango utilized an active intake manifold with a short runner valve to optimize torque and horsepower.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] At lower engine speeds, the valve was closed, resulting in improved low-end torque from the longer runners.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] At higher engine speeds, the valve was opened, diverting the incoming air into the center of the manifold.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The shorter runners resulted in improved horsepower.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Passenger cars, Jeep vehicles, as well as HEV Chrysler Aspen and HEV Dodge Durango did not use this manifold; instead, these vehicles utilized a passive intake manifold, which did not have a short runner valve.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Also, the new cylinder head came with different spark plug seats: tapered seats were replaced with gasket seats.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] This change made it impossible to use the old OE Champion RE14MCC4, so the new spark plugs that came with 5.7 HEMI became NGK LZFR5C-11.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Besides different seats, the spark plug gap grew from .039" (1.0 mm) to .043" (1.1 mm).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Engines mated to the six-speed manual transmission or used in the Ram Heavy Duty did not feature the Multi-Displacement System (MDS).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The Hemi was also available in a 6,059 cc (6.1 L; 369.7 cu in) version that was developed in 2004 for the 2005 model year Chrysler 300C SRT8.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The engine's bore × stroke was 103 mm × 90.9 mm (4.055 in × 3.579 in), and many other changes were made to allow it to produce 425 bhp (317 kW; 431 PS) at 6,200 rpm and 420 lb⋅ft (569 N⋅m) of torque at 4,800 rpm.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The engine block differed from the 5.7, with revised coolant channels and oil jets to cool the pistons.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] A forged crankshaft, lighter pistons, and strengthened connecting rods improved durability.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] A cast aluminium intake manifold was tuned for high-rpm power and did not include variable-length technology.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Chrysler's Multi-Displacement System was not used on the 6.1.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] For 2015, Chrysler introduced an all-new high performance supercharged variant of the Hemi engine, called the **Hellcat** (named after the Grumman F6F Hellcat).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] It features the same 4.09 in (103.9 mm) bore as the 6.4 L Hemi and the same 3.578 in (90.9 mm) stroke as the 5.7 L, giving it a total displacement of 6,166 cc (6.2 L; 376.3 cu in).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The supercharger is a 2,380 cc (145 cu in) twin-screw IHI unit with integrated charge coolers, capable of producing 11.6 psi (80 kPa; 0.80 bar) of boost.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] This engine is rated at 707 hp (717 PS; 527 kW) at 6,000 rpm and 650 lb⋅ft (881 N⋅m) at 4,000 rpm of torque and has a compression ratio of 9.5:1.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] This engine was the most powerful engine produced by Chrysler as well as the most powerful production engine ever in a muscle car until the Dodge Demon was introduced.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] This engine is not equipped with Chrysler's Multi-Displacement System.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] In 2017, Mopar announced that it would sell it as a crate engine under the name Hellcrate.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] A Redeye version with 797 hp (808 PS; 594 kW) debuted in the Dodge Challenger in 2019, followed by the Dodge Charger in 2021.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The 2026 and onward version of the engine found in the TRX and Rumble Bee versions of the Ram 1500 use newer equipment and produce 777 hp (788 PS; 579 kW) and 680 lb⋅ft (922 N⋅m).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The Demon version of the Hemi V8 features a number of improvements over the Hellcat variant.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] It is fitted with a larger, 2.7 L twin-screw supercharger, as well as reinforced reciprocating components, a new camshaft, and several other valvetrain upgrades.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] With these improvements, the Challenger SRT Demon is rated at 808 hp (603 kW) on 91-octane pump gasoline, and 840 horsepower when running on 100-octane unleaded racing gasoline.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Cooling is aided by a functional Air-Grabber hood scoop, as well as a unique charge cooling system that makes use of the air-conditioning coolant to lower the intake charge air temperature.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Chrysler displayed a larger and more powerful 392-cubic-inch (6.4 L) HEMI in 2005 with a factory-rated output of 525 hp (391 kW; 532 PS) and 510 lb⋅ft (691 N⋅m) torque.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] It is equipped with high-strength forged aluminum alloy pistons.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] This engine has been available since 2007, as a crate engine under the name 392 HEMI.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The production version of the 392 HEMI was developed in 2010, launched in the 2011 model year Dodge Challenger SRT8 with variable camshaft timing as well as MDS in cars with automatic transmissions.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The new 392 HEMI, codenamed "Apache," is based on the third-generation 5.7 L HEMI, codenamed "Eagle," and shares few parts with the 392 crate engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The "Apache" 6.4L features forged steel crankshaft, hypereutectic cast aluminum pistons with floating pins, 10.9:1 compression ratio, 2.14in intake valves and 1.65in exhaust valves.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Special-edition Chargers and Challengers equipped with this engine, and the engines themselves, featured "392 HEMI" badging in commemorative reference to the first-generation engine of the same displacement.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] For the 2015 model year, horsepower was increased to 485 hp (362 kW) and torque to 475 lb⋅ft (644 N⋅m) in the Charger and Challenger *SRT 392* (2015–2018) and *R/T Scat Pack* (2015–2023) models; the Grand Cherokee SRT only saw a 5 bhp increase.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Export models of the Chrysler 300 SRT retained the 470 hp (350 kW) and 470 lb⋅ft (637 N⋅m) output.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Starting in model year 2014, the Ram 2500 and 3500 trucks, and Ram 3500, 4500, and 5500 chassis-cabs offered a revised version of the 6.4 L known as the "BGE", Big Gas Engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Compared to the 6.4L in passenger cars/SUVs, the truck version is tuned for durability and a power band more suitable for hauling and towing, and compatibility with lower octane fuel.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The BGE 6.4L features a grey cast iron block shared with the 6.2L Hellcat engine, which features reinforced bulkheads and ribs.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The aluminum heads of the BGE 6.4L are also shared with the Hellcat 6.2, manufactured with additional ribs and cast from 356-T6 aluminum.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The BGE 6.4L features dished pistons to achieve a lower compression ratio of 10.0:1, vs the 10.9:1 compression ratio of the SRT variant.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The engine rpm is limited to 5800 rpm in pickup truck models, and 4660 rpm when paired to the Aisin transmission.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] In 2016, it replaced the 5.7 L as the standard gasoline engine in the chassis-cab models, and for 2019 became the standard gasoline engine in 2500 and 3500 models.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] At the 2012 North American International Auto Show in Detroit, Dodge debuted a Mopar Customized Dodge Charger "Redline" that featured a modern 426-cubic-inch (7.0 L) HEMI V8 engine rated at 590 hp (440 kW; 598 PS).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The Hellephant name is a spin on the nickname of the original 426-cubic-inch (7.0 L) HEMI, Elephant, and the modern Supercharged 6.2-liter Hellcat HEMIs.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] It is a crate engine, supercharged as standard, producing 1,000 hp (746 kW) and 950 lb⋅ft (1,288 N⋅m) of torque.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] From February to April 2005, DaimlerChrysler hosted a "What Can You HEMI?" contest promoting alternative uses of the HEMI engines.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The top five finalists include HEMI Snowblower, HEMI-Go-Round carousel, "HEMI on Ice" ice resurfacer, HEMI-Shredder, and HEMI Big Wheel (i.e., the child's tricycle of the 1970s).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] The winner was the HEMI Big Wheel, which had a 5.7 L Hemi in the back that was installed backwards; thus, reverse became the only forward gear.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/426-hemi] Plate steel was the predominant material, while a rolled tube of steel had to be utilized for the front tire because there were no such tires 4-foot (122 cm) in diameter that were as narrow as needed for this project.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] The parts, accessories, etc. for sale may or may not be manufactured by the OEM.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] The aftermarket encompasses parts for replacement, collision, appearance, and performance.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] The aftermarket provides a wide variety of parts of varying qualities and prices for nearly all vehicle makes and models.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] Consumers have the option of repairing their vehicles themselves (the "do-it-yourself" or "DIY" segment) or can take the vehicle to a professional repair facility (the "do-it-for me" or "DIFM" segment).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] The aftermarket helps keep vehicles on the road by providing consumers the choice of where they want their vehicles serviced, maintained, or customized.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] The United States automotive aftermarket covering light-, medium- and heavy-duty vehicles is estimated to be worth $516 billion (2025).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] The United States automotive aftermarket contribute more than 1.9% to GDP according to Hedges & Company.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] The aftermarket employs 4.9 million people who work at manufacturers, distributors, retailers and repair shops.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] In the United States, online sales of aftermarket accessories have increased year over year over traditional brick and mortar stores.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] In fact, according to Hedges & Company, "Total online eCommerce revenue for automotive parts and accessories in 2024 was at $42.4 billion in the US." That includes $21.7 billion from first-party 1P eCommerce websites and $20.7 billion from third-party 3P marketplaces.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] Singapore, which does not have a domestic automobile industry, is an especially important destination for businesses exporting automotive parts and accessories due to its high automobile turnover stemming from the peculiarities of its driving laws.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] High automobile turnover and the preference for new parts means that the market for remanufactured and reconditioned auto parts is very small.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] Combined with a high demand for "accessories, car-care products, prestige items, and new spare parts," Singapore's automotive aftermarket is large.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] In fact, Singapore has become a major automotive *components* manufacturing base, as several leading multinational corporations (MNCs) have established international procurement offices as well as their Southeast Asia distribution centers.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] In Canada, the automotive aftermarket is a C$19.4 billion industry that employs about 420,000 people.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] In Australia, the automotive aftermarket industry in 2013 was estimated to generate a AUD$5.2 billion turnover, with 21000 staff, and 1400 manufacturers.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] in Europe, the total volume of Independent Aftermarket (IAM) amounted to 127 billion Euros in 2015 (end-user prices without labor and tax).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] At that moment there were 54 parts traders with annual turnover over 100 mio Euros in Europe, 6 of them exceeded 1 billion Euros.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] Meeting platform for the international automotive aftermarket is the B2B trade fair Automechanika Dubai which takes place every two years in Frankfurt.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] At last edition the hot topics were connected cars, autonomous driving, alternative drives and the workshop of the future.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] Among online retailers, Amazon.com and eBay Motors are the largest sellers of aftermarket parts and accessories in the U.S. by both units sold and revenue, and are expected to grow 25% in 2014, far outstripping traditional chain stores.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] As DIY parts sales soften at the retail counter, chain stores have pushed themselves into the DIFM commercial business, eating into distributors’ and wholesalers’ market share.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] Since 2007, DIY sales at the chain stores have fallen a total of 3% to 5%, while commercial sales have brought in a double-digit sales increase.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] AutoZone’s DIFM sales in 2013 alone increased over 13%.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] Online sales of auto parts and accessories in the United States, including 3P marketplaces, are estimated at $42.4 billion in 2024.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] Automobile manufacturers have attempted to hinder or suppress automotive aftermarket sales by means of copyright or patent infringement litigation.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] For example, in *British Leyland Motor Corp. v Armstrong Patents Co.* in the UK, the House of Lords decided in 1986 that Leyland could not claim copyright infringement in order to prevent the aftermarket sale of replacement tailpipes to purchasers of those motor cars.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] In 2005 Harley-Davidson filed a patent and trademark infringement lawsuit against two aftermarket engine manufacturers producing drop-in replacements for Harley's engines, namely S&S Cycle and Delkron, Inc.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] Harley accused S&S and Delkron of copying parts for Twin Cam engines and using Harley trademarks without permission.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aftermarket-automotive] S&S argued that the suit was without any legal basis, and asserted that "a mutually beneficial relationship existed" between them and Harley.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] The **Allison Legacy Series** is a stock car racing series in the United States.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] It is based on 3/4 size scaled-down NASCAR Cup Series chassis utilizing a Mazda B-2200 truck engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] The lower-tier series has been used as a stepping stone into higher divisions.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] The cars were designed in 1996 by NASCAR driver Donnie Allison's sons, Donald, Kenny, and Ronald Allison.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] The series was conceived in 1996 by Donald, Kenny, and Ronald Allison, the sons of former NASCAR driver Donnie Allison.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] The vehicles were designed to be 3/4 size stock cars.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] Kenny Allison said that the cars were designed to be of "decent cost" and have "decent maintenance costs" yet be a class that fans can "relate to".
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] The cars began to compete regularly in 1998 with the formation of a national series.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] The national touring series is run out of the Allison Brothers shop at Salisbury, North Carolina.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] By 2004, eight regional touring series had formed in the United States, including the Maine Legacy Series which had Canadian dates in Quebec and Nova Scotia.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] The cars are typically raced on road courses and 0.5 miles (0.80 km) or less short tracks.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] Feature events are typically 50 laps or less.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] The series uses a tubular chassis with a fiberglass body.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] Body styles include a Ford Thunderbird and Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] The vehicle is near 60 inches (150 cm) wide, 12.5 feet (3.8 m) long, 42 inches (110 cm) high, with an 80 inches (200 cm) wheelbase.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] The chassis is coupled with a Mazda B2200 2.2-liter engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] The chassis must weigh 1,425 pounds (646 kg) (without the driver), and it uses 7-inch-wide (18 cm) Goodyear tires.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] As of August 2004, the vehicles were estimated to cost around $16,800 by the *Stock Car Racing Magazine*.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] Racing enhancements including an aluminum radiator, adjustable front suspension, aluminum front hubs, a quick-change rear end, steel racing wheels, and coil over shocks and springs.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] An aluminum racing seat, 5-point harness, and window nets are required for safety.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] Drivers in the series are part-time, including children who are old enough to have jobs.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] The series is often used as a development series by Late Model drivers.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] Drivers who have used the Allison Legacy Series on their way to NASCAR include Trevor Bayne, Kelly Bires, Erik Darnell, Joey Logano, David Ragan, Regan Smith, John Hunter Nemechek, and Brian Vickers.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] Chad McCumbee won the 2001 national championship and rookie of the year; he repeated as champion in the following season.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/allison-legacy-series] Timmy Hill won the 2009 U.S. national championship after winning ten races.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/alternator-auto] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Chemically, aluminium is a post-transition metal in the boron group; as is common for the group, aluminium forms compounds primarily in the +3 oxidation state.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The aluminium cation Al3+ is small and highly charged; as such, it has more polarizing power, and bonds formed by aluminium have a more covalent character.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The strong affinity of aluminium for oxygen leads to the common occurrence of its oxides in nature.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is found on Earth primarily in rocks in the crust, where it is the third-most abundant element after oxygen and silicon, rather than in the mantle, and virtually never as the free metal.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It is obtained industrially by mining bauxite, a sedimentary rock rich in aluminium minerals.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The discovery of aluminium was announced in 1825 by Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was initiated by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville in 1856.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium became much more available to the public with the Hall–Héroult process developed independently by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall in 1886, and the mass production of aluminium led to its extensive use in industry and everyday life.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In 1954, aluminium became the most produced non-ferrous metal, surpassing copper.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In the 21st century, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The standard atomic weight of aluminium is low in comparison with many other metals, giving it the low density responsible for many of its uses.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Despite its prevalence in the environment, no living thing is known to metabolize aluminium salts, but aluminium is well tolerated by plants and animals.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Because of the abundance of these salts, the potential for a biological role for them is of interest, and studies are ongoing.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium metal has an appearance ranging from silvery white to dull gray depending on its surface roughness.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium mirrors provides high reflectivity for light in the ultraviolet, visible (on par with silver), and far infrared regions.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is also good at reflecting solar radiation, although prolonged exposure to sunlight in air can deteriorate the reflectivity of the metal; this may be prevented if aluminium is anodized, which adds a protective layer of oxide on the surface.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The density of aluminium is 2.70 g/cm3, about one-third that of steel, much lower than other commonly encountered metals, making aluminium parts easily identifiable through their lightness.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium's low density compared to most other metals arises from the fact that its unit cell size is relatively large in proportion to the number of nucleons.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The only lighter metals are the metals of groups 1 and 2, which, apart from beryllium and magnesium, are too reactive for structural use (and beryllium is very toxic).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is not as strong or stiff as steel, but the low density makes up for this in the aerospace industry and for many other applications where light weight and relatively high strength are crucial.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Pure aluminium is quite soft and lacking in strength.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In most applications, various aluminium alloys are used instead because of their higher strength and hardness.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The yield strength of pure aluminium is 7–11 MPa, while aluminium alloys have yield strengths ranging from 200 MPa to 600 MPa.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is ductile, with a percent elongation of 50–70%, and malleable allowing it to be easily drawn and extruded; it is also easily machined and cast.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is an excellent thermal and electrical conductor, and the amount of aluminium required to match the same amperage in copper weighs only half as much.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is capable of superconductivity, with a superconducting critical temperature of 1.2 kelvin and a critical magnetic field of about 100 gauss (10 milliteslas).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It is paramagnetic and thus essentially unaffected by static magnetic fields.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] However, the high electrical conductivity means that it is strongly affected by alternating magnetic fields through the induction of eddy currents.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] An aluminium atom has 13 electrons with an electron configuration of [Ne] 3s2 3p1, with three electrons beyond a stable noble gas configuration.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Accordingly, the combined first three ionization energies of aluminium are far lower than the fourth ionization energy alone.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Such an electron configuration is shared with the other well-characterized members of its group, boron, gallium, indium, and thallium; it is also expected for nihonium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium can surrender its three outermost electrons in many chemical reactions (see below).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The electronegativity of aluminium is 1.61 on the Pauling scale.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] A free aluminium atom has an atomic radius of 143 pm.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] With the three outermost electrons removed, the radius shrinks to 39 pm for a 4-coordinated atom or 53.5 pm for a 6-coordinated atom.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] At standard temperature and pressure, aluminium atoms (when not affected by atoms of other elements) form a face-centered cubic crystal system bound by metallic bonding provided by atoms' outermost electrons; hence, aluminium (at these conditions) is a metal.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] This crystal system is shared by many other metals, such as lead and copper; the size of a unit cell of aluminium is comparable to that of those other metals.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] This system, however, is not shared by the other members of its group: boron has ionization energies too high to allow metallization, thallium has a hexagonal close-packed structure, and gallium and indium have unusual structures that are not close-packed like those of aluminium and thallium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The few electrons that are available for metallic bonding in aluminium are a probable cause for it being soft with a low melting point and low electrical resistivity.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium has one stable isotope, 27Al, which comprises virtually all of the naturally-occurring element.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] This is common for elements with an odd atomic number.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It is therefore a mononuclidic element for standard atomic weight, which is determined completely by that isotope.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is useful in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), as its single stable isotope (though quadrupolar) has a high NMR sensitivity.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] All other isotopes of aluminium are radioactive.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The most stable of these is 26Al, with a half-life of 717,000 years.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] While it was present along with stable 27Al in the interstellar medium from which the Solar System formed (believed to have been produced by stellar nucleosynthesis also), no detectable amount could have survived the time since the formation of the planet.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] However, minute traces of 26Al are still produced from decay of argon in the atmosphere induced by ionizing radiation of cosmic rays.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The ratio of 26Al to 10Be has been used for the radiodating of geological processes over 105 to 106 year time scales, in particular transport, deposition, sediment storage, burial times, and erosion.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Most meteorite scientists believe that the energy released by the decay of 26Al was responsible for the melting and differentiation of some asteroids after their formation 4.55 billion years ago.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The other known isotopes of aluminium, with mass numbers ranging from 20 to 43, all have half-lives less than 7 minutes, as do the four detected metastable states.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium combines characteristics of pre- and post-transition metals.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Since it has few available electrons for metallic bonding, like the heavier group 13 elements, it has the characteristic physical properties of a post-transition metal, with longer-than-expected interatomic distances.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Furthermore, as Al3+ is a small and highly charged cation, it is strongly polarizing, and bonding in aluminium compounds tends towards covalency; this behavior is similar to that of beryllium (Be2+), displaying an example of a diagonal relationship.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The underlying core of electrons under aluminium's valence shell is that of the preceding noble gas, whereas those of the heavier group 13 elements gallium, indium, thallium, and nihonium also include a filled d-subshell and in some cases a filled f-subshell.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Hence, the inner electrons of aluminium shield the valence electrons almost completely, unlike those of the heavier group 13 elements.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] As such, aluminium is the most electropositive metal in its group, and its hydroxide is in fact more basic than that of gallium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium also bears minor similarities to boron (a metalloid), which is in the same group: AlX3 compounds are valence isoelectronic to BX3 compounds (they have the same valence electronic structure), and both behave as Lewis acids and readily form adducts.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Additionally, one of the main motifs of boron chemistry is regular icosahedral structures, and aluminium forms an important part of many icosahedral quasicrystal alloys, including the Al–Zn–Mg class.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium has a high chemical affinity to oxygen, which renders it suitable for use as a reducing agent in the thermite reaction.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] A fine powder of aluminium reacts explosively on contact with liquid oxygen; under normal conditions, however, aluminium forms a thin oxide layer (~5 nm at room temperature) that protects the metal from further corrosion by oxygen, water, or dilute acid, a process termed passivation.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is not attacked by oxidizing acids because of its passivation.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] This allows aluminium to be used to store reagents such as nitric acid, concentrated sulfuric acid, and some organic acids.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In hot, concentrated hydrochloric acid, aluminium reacts with water through evolution of hydrogen, and it reacts in aqueous sodium or potassium hydroxide at room temperature to form aluminates; protective passivation under these conditions is negligible.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is also corroded by dissolved chlorides, such as common sodium chloride.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The oxide layer on aluminium is also destroyed by contact with mercury due to amalgamation or by contact with salts of some electropositive metals.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] As such, the strongest aluminium alloys are less corrosion-resistant due to galvanic reactions with alloyed copper, and aluminium's corrosion resistance is greatly reduced by aqueous salts, particularly in the presence of dissimilar metals.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium reacts with most nonmetals upon heating, forming compounds such as aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), and the aluminium halides (AlX3).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It also forms a wide range of intermetallic compounds involving metals from every group on the periodic table.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The vast majority of aluminium compounds, including all aluminium-containing minerals and all commercially significant aluminium compounds, feature aluminium in the oxidation state 3+.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The coordination number of such compounds varies, but generally Al3+ is either six- or four-coordinate.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Almost all compounds of aluminium(III) are colorless.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In aqueous solution, Al3+ exists as the hexa-aqua cation [Al(H2O)6]3+, which has an approximate Ka of 10−5.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Such solutions are acidic because this cation can act as a proton donor and progressively hydrolyze until a precipitate of aluminium hydroxide, Al(OH)3, forms.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] This is useful for clarification of water, since the precipitate nucleates on suspended particles in the water, hence removing them.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Increasing the pH even further leads to the hydroxide dissolving again as aluminate, [Al(H2O)2(OH)4]−, is formed.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium hydroxide forms both salts and aluminates and dissolves in acid and alkali, as well as on fusion with acidic and basic oxides.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] This behavior of Al(OH)3 is termed amphoterism and is characteristic of weakly basic cations that form insoluble hydroxides and whose hydrated species can also donate their protons.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] One effect of this is that aluminium salts with weak acids are hydrolyzed in water to the aquated hydroxide and the corresponding nonmetal hydride: for example, aluminium sulfide yields hydrogen sulfide.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] However, some salts like aluminium carbonate exist in aqueous solution but are unstable as such.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Only incomplete hydrolysis takes place for salts with strong acids, such as the halides, nitrate, and sulfate.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] For similar reasons, anhydrous aluminium salts cannot be made by heating their "hydrates": hydrated aluminium chloride is in fact not AlCl3·6H2O but [Al(H2O)6]Cl3, and the Al–O bonds are so strong that heating is not sufficient to break them and form Al–Cl bonds.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Unlike the structures of the three heavier trihalides, aluminium fluoride (AlF3) features six-coordinate aluminium, which explains its involatility and insolubility as well as high heat of formation.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Each aluminium atom is surrounded by six fluorine atoms in a distorted octahedral arrangement, with each fluorine atom being shared between the corners of two octahedra.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Such {AlF6} units also exist in complex fluorides such as cryolite, Na3AlF6.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] AlF3 melts at 1,290 °C (2,354 °F) and is made by reaction of aluminium oxide with hydrogen fluoride gas at 700 °C (1,300 °F).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] With heavier halides, the coordination numbers are lower.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The other trihalides are dimeric or polymeric with tetrahedral four-coordinate aluminium centers.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium trichloride (AlCl3) has a layered polymeric structure below its melting point of 192.4 °C (378 °F) but transforms on melting to Al2Cl6 dimers.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] At higher temperatures those increasingly dissociate into trigonal planar AlCl3 monomers similar to the structure of BCl3.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium tribromide and aluminium triiodide form Al2X6 dimers in all three phases and hence do not show such significant changes of properties upon phase change.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] These materials are prepared by treating aluminium with the halogen.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The aluminium trihalides form many addition compounds or complexes.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Their Lewis acidic nature makes them useful as catalysts for the Friedel–Crafts reactions.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium trichloride has major industrial uses involving this reaction, such as in the manufacture of anthraquinones and styrene.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium trichloride is also often used as the precursor for many other aluminium compounds and as a reagent for converting nonmetal fluorides into the corresponding chlorides (a transhalogenation reaction).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium forms one stable oxide with the chemical formula Al2O3, commonly called alumina.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It can be found in nature in the mineral corundum, the α-alumina phase.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Its crystalline form, corundum, is very hard (Mohs hardness 9), has a high melting point of 2,045 °C (3,713 °F), has very low volatility, is chemically inert, and is a good electrical insulator.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It is often used in abrasives (such as sandpaper) as a refractory material and in ceramics.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It is also the starting material for the electrolytic production of aluminium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Sapphire and ruby are impure corundum contaminated with trace amounts of other metals.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The two main oxide-hydroxides, AlO(OH), are boehmite and diaspore.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] There are three main trihydroxides: bayerite, gibbsite, and nordstrandite, which differ in their crystalline structure (polymorphs).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Many other intermediate and related structures are also known.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Most of these Al-O-OH systems are produced from ores by a variety of wet processes using acid and bases.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Heating the hydroxides leads to the formation of corundum.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] These materials are of central importance to the production of aluminium and are themselves extremely useful.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Some mixed oxide phases are also very useful, such as spinel (MgAl2O4), Na-β-alumina (NaAl11O17), and tricalcium aluminate (Ca3Al2O6), an important mineral phase in Portland cement.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The only stable chalcogenides under normal conditions are aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), selenide (Al2Se3), and telluride (Al2Te3).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] All three are prepared by direct reaction of their elements at about 1,000 °C (1,800 °F) and quickly hydrolyze completely in water to yield aluminium hydroxide and the respective hydrogen chalcogenide.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] As aluminium is a small atom relative to these chalcogens, these have four-coordinate tetrahedral aluminium with various polymorphs having structures related to wurtzite, with two-thirds of the possible metal sites occupied either in an orderly (α) or random (β) fashion.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The sulfide also has a γ form related to γ-alumina and an unusual high-temperature hexagonal form where half the aluminium atoms have tetrahedral four-coordination and the other half have trigonal bipyramidal five-coordination.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Four pnictides – aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium phosphide (AlP), aluminium arsenide (AlAs), and aluminium antimonide (AlSb) – are known.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] They are all III-V semiconductors isoelectronic to silicon and germanium, all of which but AlN have the zinc blende structure.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] All four can be made by high-temperature (and possibly high-pressure) direct reaction of their component elements.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium alloys well with most other metals (with the exception of most alkali metals and group 13 metals) and over 150 intermetallics with other metals are known.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Preparation involves heating fixed metals together in certain proportions, followed by gradual cooling and annealing.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Bonding in them is predominantly metallic and the crystal structure primarily depends on efficiency of packing.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] There are few compounds with lower oxidation states.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Some are aluminium(I) compounds: AlF, AlCl, AlBr, and AlI all exist in the gaseous phase when the respective trihalide is heated with aluminium, and at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] A stable derivative of aluminium monoiodide is the cyclic adduct formed with triethylamine, Al4I4(NEt3)4.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Al2O and Al2S also exist but are very unstable.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Very simple aluminium(II) compounds are invoked or observed in the reactions of Al metal with oxidants.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] For example, aluminium monoxide, AlO, has been detected in the gas phase after explosion and in stellar absorption spectra.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] More thoroughly investigated are compounds of the formula R4Al2 which contain an Al–Al bond and where R is a large organic ligand.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] A variety of compounds of empirical formula AlR3 and AlR1.5Cl1.5 exist.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The aluminium trialkyls and triaryls are either reactive, volatile, and colorless liquids or low-melting solids.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] They catch fire spontaneously in air and react with water, thus necessitating precautions when handling them.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] They often form dimers, unlike their boron analogues, but this tendency diminishes for branched-chain alkyls (e.g.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] For example, triisobutylaluminium exists as an equilibrium mixture of the monomer and dimer.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] These dimers, such as trimethylaluminium (Al2Me6), usually feature tetrahedral Al centers formed by dimerization with some alkyl group bridging between both aluminium atoms.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] They are hard acids and react readily with ligands, forming adducts.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In industry, they are mostly used in alkene insertion reactions, as discovered by Karl Ziegler, most importantly in "growth reactions" that form long-chain unbranched primary alkenes and alcohols, and in the low-pressure polymerization of ethene and propene.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] There are also some heterocyclic and cluster organoaluminium compounds involving Al–N bonds.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The industrially most important aluminium hydride is lithium aluminium hydride (LiAlH4), which is used as a reducing agent in organic chemistry.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It can be produced from lithium hydride and aluminium trichloride.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The simplest hydride, aluminium hydride or alane, is not as important.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It is a polymer with the formula (AlH3)*n*, which is in contrast to the corresponding boron hydride that is a dimer with the formula (BH3)2.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium's per-particle abundance in the Solar System is 3.15 ppm (parts per million).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It is the twelfth most abundant of all elements and third most abundant among the elements that have odd atomic numbers, after hydrogen and nitrogen.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The only stable isotope of aluminium, 27Al, is the eighteenth most abundant nucleus in the universe.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It is created almost entirely after fusion of carbon in massive stars that will later become Type II supernovas: this fusion creates 26Mg, which upon capturing free protons and neutrons, becomes aluminium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Some smaller quantities of 27Al are created in hydrogen burning shells of evolved stars, where 26Mg can capture free protons.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Essentially all aluminium now in existence is 27Al.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] 26Al was present in the early Solar System with abundance of 0.005% relative to 27Al but its half-life of 728,000 years is too short for any original nuclei to survive; 26Al is therefore extinct.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Unlike for 27Al, hydrogen burning is the primary source of 26Al, with the nuclide emerging after a nucleus of 25Mg catches a free proton.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] However, the trace quantities of 26Al that do exist are the most common gamma ray emitter in the interstellar gas; if the original 26Al were still present, gamma ray maps of the Milky Way would be brighter.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Overall, the Earth is about 1.59% aluminium by mass (seventh in abundance by mass).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium occurs in greater proportion in the Earth's crust than in the universe at large.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] This is because aluminium easily forms the oxide and becomes bound into rocks and stays in the Earth's crust, while less reactive metals sink to the core.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In the Earth's crust, aluminium is the most abundant metallic element (8.23% by mass) and the third most abundant of all elements (after oxygen and silicon).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] A large number of silicates in the Earth's crust contain aluminium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In contrast, the Earth's mantle is only 2.38% aluminium by mass.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium also occurs in seawater at a concentration of 0.41 μg/kg.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Because of its strong affinity for oxygen, aluminium is almost never found in the elemental state; instead it is found in oxides or silicates.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Feldspars, the most common group of minerals in the Earth's crust, are aluminosilicates.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium also occurs in the minerals beryl, cryolite, garnet, spinel, and turquoise.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Impurities in alumina yield gemstones: for example, chromium yields ruby and iron yields sapphire.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Native aluminium metal is extremely rare and can only be found as a minor phase in low oxygen fugacity environments, such as the interiors of certain volcanoes.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Native aluminium has been reported in cold seeps in the northeastern continental slope of the South China Sea.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It is possible that these deposits resulted from bacterial reduction of tetrahydroxoaluminate Al(OH)4−.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Although aluminium is a common and widespread element, not all aluminium minerals are economically viable sources of the metal.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Almost all metallic aluminium is produced from the ore bauxite (AlO*x*(OH)3–2*x*).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Bauxite occurs as a weathering product of low iron and silica bedrock in tropical climatic conditions.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In 2017, most bauxite was mined in Australia, China, Guinea, and India.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The history of aluminium has been shaped by usage of alum.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The first written record of alum, made by Greek historian Herodotus, dates back to the 5th century BCE.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The ancients are known to have used alum as a dyeing mordant and for city defense as a fire-resistant coating for wood.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] After the Crusades, alum, an indispensable good in the European fabric industry, was a subject of international commerce; it was imported to Europe from the eastern Mediterranean until the mid-15th century.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The nature of alum remained unknown until Swiss physician Paracelsus suggested alum was a salt of an earth of alum around 1530.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] German doctor and chemist Andreas Libavius experimentally confirmed this in 1595.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] German chemist Friedrich Hoffmann announced his belief that the base of alum was a distinct earth in 1722.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] German chemist Andreas Sigismund Marggraf synthesized alumina in 1754 by boiling clay in sulfuric acid and subsequently adding potash.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Attempts to produce aluminium date back to 1760.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The first successful attempt, however, was completed in 1824 by Danish physicist and chemist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] He reacted anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium amalgam, yielding a lump of metal looking similar to tin.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] He presented his results and demonstrated a sample of the new metal in 1825.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In 1827, German chemist Friedrich Wöhler repeated Ørsted's experiments but did not identify any aluminium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] (The reason for this inconsistency was only discovered in 1921.) He conducted a similar experiment in the same year by mixing anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium (the Wöhler process) and produced a powder of aluminium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In 1845, he was able to produce small pieces of the metal and described some physical properties of this metal.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] For many years thereafter, Wöhler was credited as the discoverer of aluminium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] As Wöhler's method could not yield great quantities of aluminium, the metal remained rare; its cost exceeded that of gold.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was established in 1856 by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville and companions.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Sainte-Claire Deville had discovered that aluminium trichloride could be reduced by sodium, which was more convenient and less expensive than potassium, which Wöhler had used.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Even then, aluminium was still not of great purity and produced aluminium differed in properties by sample.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Because of its electricity-conducting capacity, aluminium was used as the cap of the Washington Monument, completed in 1885, the tallest building in the world at the time.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The non-corroding metal cap was intended to serve as a lightning rod peak.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The first industrial large-scale production method was independently developed in 1886 by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall; it is now known as the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The Hall–Héroult process converts alumina into metal.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Austrian chemist Carl Joseph Bayer discovered a way of purifying bauxite to yield alumina, now known as the Bayer process, in 1889.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Modern production of aluminium is based on the Bayer and Hall–Héroult processes.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] As large-scale production caused aluminium prices to drop, the metal became widely used in jewelry, eyeglass frames, optical instruments, tableware, and foil, and other everyday items in the 1890s and early 20th century.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium's ability to form hard yet light alloys with other metals provided the metal with many uses at the time.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] During World War I, major governments demanded large shipments of aluminium for light strong airframes; during World War II, demand by major governments for aviation was even higher.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] From the early 20th century to 1980, the aluminium industry was characterized by cartelization, as aluminium firms colluded to keep prices high and stable.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The first aluminium cartel, the Aluminium Association, was founded in 1901 by the Pittsburgh Reduction Company (renamed Alcoa in 1907) and Aluminium Industrie AG.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The British Aluminium Company, Produits Chimiques d'Alais et de la Camargue, and Société Électro-Métallurgique de Froges also joined the cartel.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] By the mid-20th century, aluminium had become a part of everyday life and an essential component of housewares.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In 1954, production of aluminium surpassed that of copper, historically second in production only to iron, making it the most produced non-ferrous metal.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] During the mid-20th century, aluminium emerged as a civil engineering material, with building applications in both basic construction and interior finish work, and increasingly being used in military engineering, for both airplanes and armored vehicle engines.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Earth's first artificial satellite, launched in 1957, consisted of two separate aluminium semi-spheres joined and all subsequent space vehicles have used aluminium to some extent.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The aluminium can was invented in 1956 and employed as a storage for drinks in 1958.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Throughout the 20th century, the production of aluminium rose rapidly: while the world production of aluminium in 1900 was 6,800 metric tons, the annual production first exceeded 100,000 metric tons in 1916; 1,000,000 tons in 1941; 10,000,000 tons in 1971.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In the 1970s, the increased demand for aluminium made it an exchange commodity; it entered the London Metal Exchange, the oldest industrial metal exchange in the world, in 1978.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The output continued to grow: the annual production of aluminium exceeded 50,000,000 metric tons in 2013.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The real price for aluminium declined from $14,000 per metric ton in 1900 to $2,340 in 1948 (in 1998 United States dollars).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Extraction and processing costs were lowered over technological progress and the scale of the economies.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] However, the need to exploit lower-grade poorer quality deposits and the use of fast increasing input costs (above all, energy) increased the net cost of aluminium; the real price began to grow in the 1970s with the rise of energy cost.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Production moved from the industrialized countries to countries where production was cheaper.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Production costs in the late 20th century changed because of advances in technology, lower energy prices, exchange rates of the United States dollar, and alumina prices.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The BRIC countries' combined share in primary production and primary consumption grew substantially in the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] China is accumulating an especially large share of the world's production thanks to an abundance of resources, cheap energy, and governmental stimuli; it also increased its consumption share from 2% in 1972 to 40% in 2010.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In the United States, Western Europe, and Japan, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In 2021, prices for industrial metals such as aluminium have soared to near-record levels as energy shortages in China drive up costs for electricity.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The names *aluminium* and *aluminum* are derived from the word *alumine*, an obsolete term for *alumina*, the primary naturally occurring oxide of aluminium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] *Alumine* was borrowed from French, which in turn derived it from *alumen*, the classical Latin name for alum, the mineral from which it was collected.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The Latin word *alumen* stems from the Proto-Indo-European root **alu-* meaning "bitter" or "beer".
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The English name *alum* does not come directly from Latin, whereas *alumine*/*alumina* comes from the Latin word *alumen* (on declension, *alumen* changes to *alumin-*).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] British chemist Humphry Davy, who performed a number of experiments aimed to isolate the metal, is credited as the person who named the element.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The first name proposed for the metal to be isolated from alum was *alumium*, which Davy suggested in an 1808 article on his electrochemical research, published in Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It appeared that the name was created from the English word *alum* and the Latin suffix *-ium*; but it was customary then to give elements names originating in Latin, so this name was not adopted universally.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The name *alumium* was criticized by contemporary chemists from France, Germany, and Sweden, who insisted the metal should be named for the oxide, alumina, from which it would be isolated.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] One example was *Essai sur la Nomenclature chimique* (July 1811), written in French by a Swedish chemist, Jöns Jacob Berzelius, in which the name *aluminium* is given to the element that would be synthesized from alum.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] (Another article in the same journal issue also refers to the metal whose oxide is the basis of sapphire, i.e., the same metal, as to *aluminium*.) A January 1811 summary of one of Davy's lectures at the Royal Society mentioned the name *aluminium* as a possibility.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In 1812, Davy published his chemistry text *Elements of Chemical Philosophy* in which he used the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In 1812, British scientist Thomas Young wrote an anonymous review of Davy's book, in which he proposed the name *aluminium* instead of *aluminum*, which he thought had a "less classical sound".
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] This name persisted: although the *-um* spelling was occasionally used in Britain, the American scientific language used *-ium* from the start.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The French have used the spelling *aluminium* from the start.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Most scientists throughout the world used *-ium* in the 19th century; and it was entrenched in several other European languages, such as French, German, and Dutch.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In 1828, an American lexicographer, Noah Webster, entered only the *aluminum* spelling in his *American Dictionary of the English Language*.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In the 1830s, the *-um* spelling gained usage in the United States; by the 1860s, it had become the more common spelling there outside science.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In 1892, Hall used the *-um* spelling in his advertising handbill for his new electrolytic method of producing the metal, despite his constant use of the *-ium* spelling in all the patents he filed between 1886 and 1903.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It is unknown whether this spelling was introduced by mistake or intentionally, but Hall preferred *aluminum* since its introduction because it resembled *platinum*, the name of a prestigious metal.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] By 1890, both spellings had been common in the United States, the *-ium* spelling being slightly more common; by 1895, the situation had reversed; by 1900, *aluminum* had become twice as common as *aluminium*; in the next decade, the *-um* spelling dominated American usage.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In 1925, the American Chemical Society adopted the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) adopted *aluminium* as the standard international name for the element in 1990.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In 1993, they recognized *aluminum* as an acceptable variant; the most recent 2005 edition of the IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry also acknowledges this spelling.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] IUPAC official publications use the *-ium* spelling as primary, and they list both where it is appropriate.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Their usage is currently regional: *aluminum* dominates in the United States and Canada; *aluminium* is prevalent in the rest of the English-speaking world.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] German physicist Ludwig Wilhelm Gilbert had proposed *Thonerde-metall*, after the German *Thonerde* for alumina, in his *Annalen der Physik* but that name never caught on at all even in Germany.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Richards in 1891 found just one occurrence of *argillium* in Swedish, from the French *argille* for clay.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The production of aluminium starts with the extraction of bauxite rock from the ground.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The bauxite is processed and transformed using the Bayer process into alumina, which is then processed using the Hall–Héroult process, resulting in the final aluminium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium production is highly energy-consuming, and so the producers tend to locate smelters in places where electric power is both plentiful and inexpensive.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Production of one kilogram of aluminium requires 7 kilograms of oil energy equivalent, as compared to 1.5 kilograms for steel and 2 kilograms for plastic.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] As of 2024, the world's largest producers of aluminium were China, India, Russia, Canada, and the United Arab Emirates, while China is by far the top producer of aluminium with a world share of over 55%.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] According to the International Resource Panel's Metal Stocks in Society report, the global per capita stock of aluminium in use in society (i.e. in cars, buildings, electronics, etc.) is 80 kg (180 lb).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Much of this is in more-developed countries (350–500 kg (770–1,100 lb) per capita) rather than less-developed countries (35 kg (77 lb) per capita).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Bauxite is converted to alumina by the Bayer process.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Bauxite is blended for uniform composition and then is ground fine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] After this reaction, the slurry is at a temperature above its atmospheric boiling point.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It is cooled by removing steam as pressure is reduced.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The bauxite residue is separated from the solution and discarded.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The solution, free of solids, is seeded with small crystals of aluminium hydroxide; this causes decomposition of the [Al(OH)4]− ions to aluminium hydroxide.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] After about half of aluminium has precipitated, the mixture is sent to classifiers.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Small crystals of aluminium hydroxide are collected to serve as seeding agents; coarse particles are converted to alumina by heating; the excess solution is removed by evaporation, (if needed) purified, and recycled.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The conversion of alumina to aluminium is achieved by the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] In this energy-intensive process, a solution of alumina in a molten (940 and 970 °C (1,720 and 1,780 °F)) mixture of cryolite (Na3AlF6) with calcium fluoride is electrolyzed to produce metallic aluminium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The liquid aluminium sinks to the bottom of the solution and is tapped off, and usually cast into large blocks called aluminium billets for further processing.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Anodes of the electrolysis cell are made of carbon—the most resistant material against fluoride corrosion—and either bake at the process or are prebaked.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The former, also called Söderberg anodes, are less power-efficient and fumes released during baking are costly to collect, which is why they are being replaced by prebaked anodes even though they save the power, energy, and labor to prebake the cathodes.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Carbon for anodes should be preferably pure so that neither aluminium nor the electrolyte is contaminated with ash.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Despite carbon's resistivity against corrosion, it is still consumed at a rate of 0.4–0.5 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Cathodes are made of anthracite; high purity for them is not required because impurities leach only very slowly.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The cathode is consumed at a rate of 0.02–0.04 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] A cell is usually terminated after 2–6 years following a failure of the cathode.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The Hall–Heroult process produces aluminium with a purity of above 99%.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Further purification can be done by the Hoopes process.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] This process involves the electrolysis of molten aluminium with a sodium, barium, and aluminium fluoride electrolyte.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The resulting aluminium has a purity of 99.99%.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Electric power represents about 20 to 40% of the cost of producing aluminium, depending on the location of the smelter.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium production consumes roughly 5% of electricity generated in the United States.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Because of this, alternatives to the Hall–Héroult process have been researched, but none has turned out to be economically feasible.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Recovery of the metal through recycling has become an important task of the aluminium industry.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Recycling was a low-profile activity until the late 1960s, when the growing use of aluminium beverage cans brought it to public awareness.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Recycling involves melting the scrap, a process that requires only 5% of the energy used to produce aluminium from ore, though a significant part (up to 15% of the input material) is lost as dross (ash-like oxide).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] An aluminium stack melter produces significantly less dross, with values reported below 1%.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] White dross from primary aluminium production and from secondary recycling operations still contains useful quantities of aluminium that can be extracted industrially.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The process produces aluminium billets, together with a highly complex waste material.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It reacts with water, releasing a mixture of gases including, among others, acetylene, hydrogen sulfide and significant amounts of ammonia.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Despite these difficulties, the waste is used as a filler in asphalt and concrete.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Its potential for hydrogen production has also been considered and researched.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The global production of aluminium in 2016 was 58.8 million metric tons.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It exceeded that of any other metal except iron (1,231 million metric tons).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is almost always alloyed, which markedly improves its mechanical properties, especially when tempered.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] For example, the common aluminium foils and beverage cans are alloys of 92% to 99% aluminium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The main alloying agents for both wrought and cast aluminium are copper, zinc, magnesium, manganese, and silicon (e.g., duralumin) with the levels of other metals in a few percent by weight.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is the main substitute to copper and its applications to the traditional domains of copper have seen increased interest when copper prices are high such as in 2011–2014 and 2021.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] There is a competition in the use of aluminium and copper in the automotive industry, but in other uses such as in the construction industry and in underground and submarine cables aluminium has been largely unable to compete with copper.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The great majority (about 90%) of aluminium oxide is converted to metallic aluminium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Being a very hard material (Mohs hardness 9), alumina is widely used as an abrasive; being extraordinarily chemically inert, it is useful in highly reactive environments such as high pressure sodium lamps.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium oxide is commonly used as a catalyst for industrial processes; e.g. the Claus process to convert hydrogen sulfide to sulfur in refineries and to alkylate amines.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Many industrial catalysts are supported by alumina, meaning that the expensive catalyst material is dispersed over a surface of the inert alumina.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Another principal use is as a drying agent or absorbent.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Several sulfates of aluminium have industrial and commercial application.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium sulfate (in its hydrate form) is produced on the annual scale of several millions of metric tons.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] About two-thirds is consumed in water treatment.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] The next major application is in the manufacture of paper.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] It is also used as a mordant in dyeing, in pickling seeds, deodorizing of mineral oils, in leather tanning, and in production of other aluminium compounds.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Two kinds of alum, ammonium alum and potassium alum, were formerly used as mordants and in leather tanning, but their use has significantly declined following availability of high-purity aluminium sulfate.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Anhydrous aluminium chloride is used as a catalyst in chemical and petrochemical industries, the dyeing industry, and in synthesis of various inorganic and organic compounds.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Aluminium hydroxychlorides are used in purifying water, in the paper industry, and as antiperspirants.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p01] Sodium aluminate is used in treating water and as an accelerator of solidification of cement.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Despite its widespread occurrence in the Earth's crust, aluminium has no known function in biology.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] At pH 6–9 (relevant for most natural waters), aluminium precipitates out of water as the hydroxide and is hence not available; most elements behaving this way have no biological role or are toxic.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Aluminium sulfate has an LD50 of 6207 mg/kg (oral, mouse).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Aluminium is classified as a non-carcinogen by the United States Department of Health and Human Services.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] A review published in 1988 said that there was little evidence that normal exposure to aluminium presents a risk to healthy adult, and a 2014 multi-element toxicology review was unable to find deleterious effects of aluminium consumed in amounts not greater than 40 mg/day per kg of body mass.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Most ingested aluminium is eliminated in feces, and much of what enters the bloodstream is excreted in urine; however, not all absorbed or parenterally administered aluminium is cleared through urinary excretion.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Aluminium, although rarely, can cause vitamin D-resistant osteomalacia, erythropoietin-resistant microcytic anemia, and central nervous system alterations.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] People with kidney insufficiency are especially at a risk.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Chronic ingestion of hydrated aluminium silicates (for excess gastric acidity control) may result in aluminium binding to intestinal contents and increased elimination of other metals, such as iron or zinc; sufficiently high doses (>50 g/day) can cause anemia.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] During the 1988 Camelford water pollution incident, people in Camelford had their drinking water contaminated with aluminium sulfate for several weeks.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] A final report into the incident in 2013 concluded it was unlikely that this had caused long-term health problems.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Aluminium has been suspected of being a possible cause of Alzheimer's disease, but research into this for over 40 years has found, as of 2018, no good evidence of causal effect.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Aluminium increases estrogen-related gene expression in human breast cancer cells cultured in the laboratory.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] In very high doses, aluminium is associated with altered function of the blood–brain barrier.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] A small percentage of people have contact allergies to aluminium and experience itchy red rashes, headache, muscle pain, joint pain, poor memory, insomnia, depression, asthma, irritable bowel syndrome, or other symptoms upon contact with products containing aluminium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Exposure to powdered aluminium or aluminium welding fumes can cause pulmonary fibrosis.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Fine aluminium powder can ignite or explode, posing another workplace hazard.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Drinking water contains more aluminium than solid food; however, aluminium in food may be absorbed more than aluminium from water.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Dietary exposure in Europeans averages to 0.2–1.5 mg/kg/week but can be as high as 2.3 mg/kg/week.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Higher exposure levels of aluminium are mostly limited to plumbers, masons, electrical workers, machinists, and surgeons.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Consumption of antacids, antiperspirants, vaccines, and cosmetics provide possible routes of exposure.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Consumption of acidic foods or liquids with aluminium enhances aluminium absorption, and maltol has been shown to increase the accumulation of aluminium in nerve and bone tissues.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] In case of suspected sudden intake of a large amount of aluminium, the only treatment is deferoxamine mesylate which may be given to help eliminate aluminium from the body by chelation therapy.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] However, this should be applied with caution as this reduces not only aluminium body levels, but also those of other metals such as copper or iron.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] High levels of aluminium occur near mining sites; small amounts of aluminium are released to the environment at coal-fired power plants or incinerators.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Aluminium in the air is washed out by the rain or normally settles down but small particles of aluminium remain in the air for a long time.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Acidic precipitation is the main natural factor to mobilize aluminium from natural sources and the main reason for the environmental effects of aluminium; however, the main factor of presence of aluminium in salt and freshwater are the industrial processes that also release aluminium into air.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] In water, aluminium acts as a toxic agent on gill-breathing animals such as fish when the water is acidic, in which aluminium may precipitate on gills, which causes loss of plasma- and hemolymph ions leading to osmoregulatory failure.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Organic complexes of aluminium may be easily absorbed and interfere with metabolism in mammals and birds, even though this rarely happens in practice.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Aluminium is primary among the factors that reduce plant growth on acidic soils.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Although it is generally harmless to plant growth in pH-neutral soils, in acid soils the concentration of toxic Al3+ cations increases and disturbs root growth and function.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Wheat has developed a tolerance to aluminium, releasing organic compounds that bind to harmful aluminium cations.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Sorghum is believed to have the same tolerance mechanism.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Aluminium production possesses its own challenges to the environment on each step of the production process.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] The major challenge is the emission of greenhouse gases.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] These gases result from electrical consumption of the smelters and the byproducts of processing.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] The most potent of these gases are perfluorocarbons, namely CF4 and C2F6, from the smelting process.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] Biodegradation of metallic aluminium is extremely rare; most aluminium-corroding organisms do not directly attack or consume the aluminium, but instead produce corrosive wastes.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] The fungus *Geotrichum candidum* can consume the aluminium in compact discs.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/aluminum-p02] The bacterium *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* and the fungus *Cladosporium resinae* are commonly detected in aircraft fuel tanks that use kerosene-based fuels (not avgas), and laboratory cultures can degrade aluminium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] The **American-Canadian Tour** (**ACT**) is an independent regional stock car racing series based in the northeastern United States, and Eastern Canada.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] The American-Canadian Tour was founded in 1979 and conducts professionally-run stock car racing events across New England and Quebec.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] In 1979, famed television and radio journalist Ken Squier and business partner Tom Curley formed the North Tour sanctioned by NASCAR for Late Model Sportsman-type cars.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] Stars of the day included New England drivers Beaver and Bobby Dragon, Dave Dion, and Dick McCabe; Canada’s Jean-Paul Cabana and Claude Leclerc; and invaders Robbie Crouch of Tampa, Florida and Chuck Bown of Portland, Oregon.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] Southern stars Butch Lindley, Bill Dennis, Harry Gant, and Tommy Ellis were frequent visitors to NASCAR North Tour events, along with national icons Bobby Allison, Buddy Baker, and Dale Earnhardt.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] After the NASCAR sanction dissolved at the end of 1985, Curley incorporated his roster of teams into the independent American-Canadian Tour in 1986 and made a total changeover from the NASCAR Late Model Sportsman to the Pro Stock cars used throughout the country.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] In 1987, Curley’s ACT aligned with Rex Robbins’ American Speed Association (ASA) of the Midwest and Bob Harmon’s All-Pro Series of the southeast, forming the Stock Car Connection.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] With General Motors stepping up its commitment to ACT in 1989, the GM Motorsport National Stock Car Series was formed in Canada, offering large purses, even larger point funds, and coast-to-coast television coverage.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] Budweiser created the Bud Triple Crown as part of the GM Series, and paid Junior Hanley over $50,000 in 1991 and again in 1992 for sweeping the series.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] During Hanley’s ACT Championship years from 1991–93, the Ontario driver earned more than $700,000 in winnings.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] The current American-Canadian Tour Late Models utilize a modern, cost-effective program that creates side-by-side action and has built one of the more prominent short track series in North America.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] Beginning in 1992 and taking center stage in 1996, the Late Models have introduced many concepts used in several disciplines of short track racing.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] ACT developed one of the first “spec” engine programs in 1999 as a cost-saving option for local and regional racers.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] After successful testing in the early 2000s, most teams, tracks and promoters both regionally and nationally have made the switch.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] The “spec” engine program expanded to include a Ford option in 2010 and added the popular GM ‘602’ in 2018.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] A similar cost-saving “spec” program exists with Koni and QA1 shock absorbers as well as a uniform Hoosier Racing Tire utilized by the Tour and its partner tracks.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] For their efforts in the growth of stock car racing, both Squier and Curley have been inducted into the New England Auto Racers Hall of Fame and the Vermont Sports Hall of Fame.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] In 2004, ACT founder Tom Curley was voted by more than 1,000 race promoters across the continent as the Auto Racing Promoter of the Year.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] In 2018 Ken Squier was ceremoniously inducted into the NASCAR Hall of Fame in Charlotte, North Carolina for his contributions to the growth of the sport on a national, and international, level.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] ACT lost its leader in May of 2017 when a decades-long battle with COPD claimed Tom Curley.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] Ken Squier died in November 2023 after battling multiple health problems for several years.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] In November 2017, the American-Canadian Tour changed ownership for the first time in its storied history as former racer Cris Michaud and Vermont businessman Pat Malone took charge of the sanctioning body after partnering to purchase Vermont’s Thunder Road earlier that season.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] The partnership also purchased New Hampshire’s White Mountain Motorsports Park in 2019.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] In recent years ACT has competed at tracks across New England, Quebec, Virginia, North Carolina and Florida.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] Partnering with the Maine-based Pro All Stars Series (PASS), the two sanctioning bodies have co-promoted events at Thompson Speedway (CT) since 2020.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] During the 2023 season, ACT fans saw some of the greatest competition in the Northeast.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] The American-Canadian Tour averaged 33.3 cars per event in 2023 with a season-high 49 teams attempting to qualify for the season-ending event at Connecticut's Waterford Speedbowl in October.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] There was plenty of action leading up to the end.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] After winning in a March exhibition run at North Carolina’s Hickory Motor Speedway, Derek Gluchacki successfully defended his Northeast Classic victory at New Hampshire Motor Speedway by just 0.060-seconds ahead of fellow Bay Stater Tom Carey III.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] The 25th annual Community Bank 150 at Thunder Road featured the most lead changes of the season at 13 as three-time 'King of the Road' Jason Corliss battled up from a 17th-place starting position to take the home-cooking win.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] The sixth annual Milton CAT Midsummer Classic 250 again wowed as 42 cars were whittled down to a 31-car starting field at White Mountain Motorsports Park that saw Last Chance winner Jesse Switser do the impossible and take down the victory!
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] Switser joined Gabe Brown and Brandon Barker as first-time American-Canadian Tour winners in 2023.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] Competitors, officials, and fans alike eagerly awaited the 2024 season.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] ACT-sanctioned racing can also be found at Thunder Road International SpeedBowl (VT), White Mountain Motorsports Park (NH) and Thompson Speedway Motorsports Park (CT) along with the touring Serie ACT Quebec in Canada and the US-Based ACT Tri-State Flying Tiger Series.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] ACT introduced ACT Sportsman Quebec in 2025, which will race exclusively at Autodrome Montmagny.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] After a five year hiatus, partially due to the COVID-19 pandemic and subsequent international border closure, the Serie ACT Quebec series returned in 2023 for a 10-race schedule.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/american-canadian-tour] Split evenly between Quebec bullrings Autodrome Chaudiere and Autodrome Montmagny, Serie ACT Quebec brought a permanent presence back to Canada for the ACT sanctioning body.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] A **replacement automobile engine** is an engine or a major part of one that is sold alone, without the other parts required to make a functional car (for example a drivetrain).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] These engines are produced either as aftermarket parts or as reproductions of an engine that has gone out of production.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Replacement engines are used to replace classic car engines that are in poor condition or broken, or to install a more powerful or more fuel efficient engine in a vehicle.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Replacement engines are often used to make old cars more reliable for daily driving.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Classic car hobbyists may also install reproductions of a rare powerplant in a classic car (this is most often seen in Mopar muscle cars that have the 426 Hemi installed into them).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Aftermarket engines are used in many forms of motorsport.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Some late model racecar series use "crate engines" many of which are made by independent firms.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] This ensures that drivers all have similarly powered racecars.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Legends and Allison Legacy Series cars also use sealed crate motors.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] A **short block** is an engine sub-assembly comprising the portion of the cylinder block below the head gasket but above the oil pan, which usually includes the assembled engine block, crankshaft, connecting rods, and pistons with piston rings properly installed.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] An in-block cam engine short block includes the camshaft, timing gear, and any balance shafts.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Overhead cam engines don't include those parts.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Short block engines became popular after World War II, when mass production led to great consistency between individual engines; before then, most engines were hand-built and had idiosyncratic variations.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Short blocks became less popular after the 1970s when overhead camshaft (OHC) engines became the norm, as the rational unit of replacement was the long block, which includes the head, camshaft and valve gear.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] A short block is the preferred replacement component for a worn-out engine that requires major servicing beyond the capabilities of a local repair garage, when instead a machine shop may be needed.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The short block represents the major wear items of an engine: piston rings, and potentially a rebore of the cylinder bores or replacement liners, together with reground bearings on the crankshaft.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Although replacing the rings or bearing shells was at one time considered typical garage work, the need for a boring or crank grinding machine now exceed the capabilities of a standard automotive repair garage.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] A short block includes the preassembled set of major parts needed that generally exceed the capability of the garage, in one item.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The third item sometimes requiring machining, the re-cutting of valve seats in the cylinder head, was less frequently needed.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Grinding of valves to fit was once a regular garage task, as was light re-cutting with hand tools, when cast iron seats were common.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Once steel seat inserts came into use, either as a result of the switch to unleaded petrol in the 1970s or fitted into high-performance aluminium heads, machining of heads and the replacement of seats became equally commonly required.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Aluminium cylinder heads could also be damaged by warping after overheating, often requiring machining to re-flatten them.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] A short block has advantages over dismantling the engine and sending the crankshaft and other related automotive parts away for rework.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] It is usually quicker to obtain, requiring only a single shipment, rather than having to ship parts to and from the machine shop and the interim time spent at the shop to re-machine those parts.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The short block would also have been built in a workshop that was hopefully cleaner and more organised for the specialism of engine building.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Sidevalves were pre-eminent before the short block appeared as a common item, and they also offered little saving by omitting the (simple) head.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] A **long block** is an engine sub-assembly that consists of the assembled short block with crankshaft, cylinder head, camshaft (usually), and valve train.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] A long block does not include the fuel system, electrical, intake, and exhaust components, as well as other components.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] A long block may include the balancer/damper, timing cover, oil pan and valve covers.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] A long block engine replacement typically requires swapping out parts from the original engine to the long block.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] These parts can include the oil pan, timing cover, valve covers, intake manifold, emission-control parts, carburetor or fuel injection system, the exhaust manifold(s), alternator, starter, power steering pump (if any), and air conditioner compressor (if any).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Technically, a "crate engine" or "crate motor" is any automobile engine that is shipped to the installer in a crate, which can include short or long block configurations.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] For this article, a crate engine is defined as a fully-assembled engine that includes more than what is typically installed on a long block; the exact configuration will vary by vendor.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] It is also sometimes known as a "deluxe long block", which usually includes the fuel and intake system, distributor, oil pan, and ignition system.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] In some cases, exhaust manifold(s) and the water pump are included.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Crate engines are manufactured by many different companies, but they all share the same characteristics of being complete engines nearly ready to install once removed from the crate.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Generally a crate engine still will require additional parts to be fitted, which can range from minor (engine oil dipstick) to major (intake manifold and fuel injection system), depending on the engine package purchased and the targeted vehicle application.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] This type of engine has various applications including general replacement, hot rod builds, and motorsports competition.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Crate engines are often seen as an economical and more reliable solution as opposed to engine overhauls or custom builds.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Such engines are built by specialist engine builders, working in clean and well-equipped workshops, rather than general purpose repair garages.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Crate engines may be either brand new, or substantially rebuilt.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] If rebuilt, they will have been rebuilt to an extent such that they are considered to be of equal quality, reliability and expected lifetime as a new engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Crate engines are well suited in many different vehicle platforms.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Crate engines are often seen as an economical choice no matter what the application is.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] In general automobile engine replacement, a crate engine is often very competitively priced when compared to the cost of a full rebuild of a faulty engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] It is also quicker to ship from stock than to wait an equal time for parts, then to begin a rebuild.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Installers often opt for the crate engine because of the cost and ease of replacement.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Crate engines are typically a bolt-in replacement with no internal work being performed to the engine compared to a complete overhaul that requires internal part replacement by trained mechanics.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Hot Rod and other custom street applications also often choose a crate engine because of the higher value when compared to a custom built engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] In motorsports, the crate engine option has become very popular for various reasons.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Crate engines are often a more affordable option when compared to a purpose-built race engine so budget racers often go this route.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The crate engine also has developed a large fan base in many different racing series because of the competitive racing.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] As all racers in the field have identical engines, the races are won by driver's talent and chassis setup, and not the amount of horsepower a team can afford to build into their engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] In general, simply swapping an internal combustion engine for an electric traction motor is not sufficient; a complete electric vehicle (EV) drivetrain conversion also requires installation of a storage battery, inverter, reduction gear, and controller.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Most of these separate components can be packaged with the motor in a unit that is dimensionally compatible with the existing engine compartment, but the battery is usually the bulkiest, heaviest component of an EV powertrain and can create a significant challenge for fitment.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] In recent years, the restoration and EV conversion of a classic car has become known as an *electromod*, a portmanteau of electrification and restomod.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Hobbyists have been converting cars to EVs since at least the 1960s.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Many recent non-factory electromods are implemented by extracting and adapting the complete drivetrain (traction motor(s), battery, controller, and inverter) from an existing mass-produced EV, such as Tesla.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] East Coast Defender demonstrated a Tesla EV-sourced powertrain conversion of a 1969–96 Range Rover Classic, developed with Electric Classic Cars, to *Motor Trend* in 2021.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] In October 2019 there were no purpose-built crate engine EV kits available commercially, but such projects were in development.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] For example, EV West announced their Revolt Tesla Crate Motor in 2020, which married an electric traction motor from Tesla with a gear reduction unit and ended in a universal joint yoke, a suitable interface for a driveshaft.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Mechanically, the motor is fitted with mounts compatible with Chevrolet small-block engines to take advantage of numerous small-block repower kits.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Previously in 2018, Chevrolet Performance advanced an "electric crate motor" concept with the unveiling of the eCOPO Camaro at that year's SEMA show.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The eCOPO Camaro was a 2019 COPO Camaro which was equipped with a pair of BorgWarner HVH250-150 motor assemblies instead of the conventional piston engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The electric traction motor essentially served as a drop-in replacement with the same bellhousing bolt pattern and crankshaft flange as the LS engine family, so the car retained the same transmission, driveshaft, and axles as the conventional COPO Camaro.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] At the 2019 SEMA show, Chevrolet continued to develop the concept, following up with the E-10 Concept, which used the powertrains from two Bolts repackaged into in a restored 1962 C-10 pickup truck.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The following year for SEMA, Chevrolet showcased the "Electric Connect and Cruise" eCrate package in October 2020, which included the main drivetrain components of a single Bolt (motor, battery, controller, and inverter), and was demonstrated as a retrofit to a restored 1977 K5 Blazer.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The kit was scheduled to go on sale in the second half of 2021.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The Bolt motor is modified by removing the differential and reduction gear unit, then fitting an adapter plate and crank flange, allowing it to bolt to a conventional transmission.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Together with the controller and inverter, the motor occupies approximately the same space as a small-block V8; the 900 lb (410 kg) battery presents a greater challenge for packaging, which is why the initial development has focused on trucks.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] As of July 2022, it was still being explored as a "future business opportunity", according to Chevrolet Vice President Scott Bell.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] In November 2021, Ford Performance released the "Eluminator" 210 kW (281 hp) crate EV motor, which was the same traction motor used in the Ford Mustang Mach-E GT Performance Edition and used to power the 1978 F-100 Eluminator restomod pickup truck.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] As of 3 November 2021, it was available for pre-order but not yet shipping.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] General Motors began developing several small block crate race car engines in 2001 and they were released into production in 2002.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The engines are sealed and repairs being done by certified rebuilders.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The Chevrolet engine debuted in 2002 with part number 1958602 and sold for a little under $4000 in 2012.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] It has 350 cubic inch displacement via a 4.000 inch bore and 3.480 inch stroke.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The 602 engine is equipped with iron heads, a cast-iron block, and aluminum pistons.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] It produces about 350 horsepower and 390 foot-pounds of torque at 9.1:1 compression.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Applications for this engine include: IMCA Hobby Stock, IMCA Northern Sport Modified, IMCA Southern Sport Modified, Mid-American Stock cars.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Northeastern (United States) Sportman, Crate Racing USA, and others.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The Chevrolet engine has part number 88959603.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] It has 355 cubic inch displacement and 405 foot pounds of torque at 10.1:1 compression.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The 603 engine is equipped with aluminum heads, steel crank, and high silicon pistons.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The American Canadian Tour (ACT) late model sportsman utilize this engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The Chevrolet engine debuted in 2002 with part number 88958604 and sold for about $5000 in 2012.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] The 604 engine is equipped with aluminum heads, forged steel crankshaft, and an aluminum intake.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] It produces about 400 horsepower and 400 foot-pounds of torque with a 9.6:1 compression.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Applications for this engine includes IMCA Modifieds (starting in 2013), CRA All Stars Tour (allowed but not required), United Crate Racing Alliance, Big 8 Series, RUSH Late Models, Crate Racing USA, and others.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] New castings of some engines are sometimes produced by independent companies.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] These blocks commonly replace rare or popular designs for aftermarket rebuilding, especially when the original is no longer produced.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] They are sometimes available in aluminum instead of original iron, or in stronger alloys.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automobile-engine-replacement] Often they imitate the larger available displacements that were produced in small numbers or allow for displacements never available.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] A company in New York City in the United States first offered the installation of air conditioning for cars in 1933.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Most of their customers operated limousines and luxury cars.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] On 7 October 1935, Ralph Peo of Houde Engineering, Buffalo, New York, applied for a patent for an "Air Cooling Unit for Automobiles".
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] In 1939, Packard became the first automobile manufacturer to offer an optional air conditioning unit in its 1940 model year cars.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] These bulky units were manufactured by Bishop and Babcock (B&B), of Cleveland, Ohio and were ordered on approximately 2,000 cars.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The "Bishop and Babcock Weather Conditioner" also incorporated a heater.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Cars ordered with this option were shipped from Packard's East Grand Boulevard facility to the B&B factory where the installation was performed.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Once complete, the car was shipped to a local dealer for delivery to customers.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Packard warranted and supported this conversion.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The 1953 Chrysler Imperial was one of the first production cars in twelve years to offer modern automobile air conditioning as an option, following tentative experiments by Packard in 1940 and Cadillac in 1941.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Walter Chrysler had seen to the invention of Airtemp air conditioning in the 1930s for the Chrysler Building, and had offered it on cars in 1941-42, and again in 1951-52.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The Airtemp was more advanced than rival automobile air conditioners by 1953.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] It was operated by a single switch on the dashboard marked with low, medium, and high positions.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] As the highest capacity unit available at that time, the system was capable of quickly cooling the passenger compartment and also reducing humidity, dust, pollen, and tobacco smoke.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The system drew in more outside air than contemporary systems; thus, reducing the staleness associated with automotive air conditioning at the time.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Instead of plastic tubes mounted on the rear window package shelf as on GM cars, small ducts directed cool air toward the ceiling of the car where it filtered down around the passengers instead of blowing directly on them, a feature that modern cars have lost.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Cadillac, Buick, and Oldsmobile added air conditioning as an option on some of their models for the 1953 model year.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] All of these Frigidaire systems used separate engine and trunk mounted components.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] In 1954, the Nash Ambassador was the first American automobile to have a front-end, fully integrated heating, ventilating, and air-conditioning system.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The Nash-Kelvinator corporation used its experience in refrigeration to introduce the automobile industry's first compact and affordable, single-unit heating and air conditioning system optional for its Nash models.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] This was the first mass market system with controls on the dash and an electric clutch.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] This system was also compact and serviceable with all of its components installed under the hood or in the cowl area.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Combining heating, cooling, and ventilating, the new air conditioning system for the Nash cars was called the "All-Weather Eye".
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] This followed the marketing name of "Weather Eye" for Nash's fresh-air automotive heating and ventilating system that was first used in 1938.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] With a single thermostatic control, the Nash passenger compartment air cooling option was "a good and remarkably inexpensive" system.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The system had cold air for passengers enter through dash-mounted vents.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Nash's exclusive "remarkable advance" was not only the "sophisticated" unified system, but also its $345 price that beat all other systems.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Most competing systems used a separate heating system and an engine-mounted compressor, driven by the engine crankshaft via a belt, with an evaporator in the car's trunk to deliver cold air through the rear parcel shelf and overhead vents.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] General Motors offered a front-mounted air conditioning system made by its Harrison Division on 1954 Pontiacs with a straight-eight engine.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] It was very expensive and not a fully integrated system with separate controls and ducts for air distribution.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The heater core continued to be a separate "Venti-Seat" or under the front seat system with its own controls.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The innovation was adopted quickly and by 1960 about 20% of all cars in the U.S. had air-conditioning, with the percentage increasing to 80% in the warm areas of the Southwest.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Cadillac introduced the industry's first Comfort Control which was a completely automatic heating and cooling system set by dial thermostat for the 1964 model year.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] American Motors Corporation (AMC) made air conditioning standard equipment on all AMC Ambassadors starting with the 1968 model year, an innovation in the mass market with the base prices of the cars starting at $2,671.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] At the time, air conditioning was standard only on Cadillac limousines and Rolls-Royces.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] By 1969, 54% of domestic automobiles were equipped with air conditioning, a feature needed not only for passenger comfort, but also to increase the car's resale value.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Air-conditioning for automobiles came into widespread use in the United States starting from the 1980s.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Adoption was slower elsewhere; in 1990 less than eight percent of cars sold in Europe were thus equipped.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] A car cooler is an automobile evaporative cooler, sometimes referred to as a swamp cooler.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Most are aftermarket relatively inexpensive accessories consisting of an external window-mounted metal cylinder without moving parts, but internal under the dashboard or center floor units with an electric fan are available.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] It was an early type of automobile air conditioner and is not used in modern cars relying on refrigerative systems to cool the interior.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] To cool the air it used latent heat (in other words, cooling by water evaporation).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Water inside the device evaporates and in the process transfers heat from the surrounding air.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The cool moisture-laden air is then directed to the inside of the car.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The evaporate "cooling" effect decreases with humidity because the air is already saturated with water.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Therefore, the lower the humidity, such as in dry desert regions, the better the system works.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Car coolers were popular, especially among summer tourists visiting or crossing the southwestern United States states of California, Arizona, Texas, New Mexico, and Nevada.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] R-12, the first automotive air conditioning refrigerant, was invented in 1928 by a team of scientists put together by Thomas Midgley, Jr.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The team of scientists set out to create refrigerants which led to the invention of chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) and hydrochlorofluorocarbons (HCFCs).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] From these two inventions, two refrigerants were created, R-12 and R-22.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] For many decades, both of these refrigerants could commonly be found in households and businesses.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] R-12 was also used in automotive air conditioning systems because it was the first safe non-flammable refrigerant.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] This refrigerant was the industry standard until the 1970s when scientists discovered that R-12 contained chlorine which depleted the ozone layer in the earth’s atmosphere.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] When R-12 was released from either a leak in systems or improperly disposing of contaminated freon, the gaseous freon would go up into the atmosphere.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Chlorine molecules from the refrigerant would break up ozone molecules in the atmosphere, which produced holes in the ozone, that in turn contributed to the destruction of the ozone layer.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] R-12 continued to be used until a new refrigerant could be invented that had fewer negative effects.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] R-12 was used in automotive air conditioning systems until the mid-90s when production was banned by the government and replaced with a new refrigerant, R-134a.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] R-12 can still be bought and sold but is no longer produced.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] This makes R-12 very expensive and hard to find.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] R-12’s global warming potential number is very large at about 11,000.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The second automotive air conditioning refrigerant invented was R-134a.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] R-134a is a hydrofluorocarbon refrigerant that contains fluorine and hydrogen.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The successor to R-12, R-134a was a new refrigerant that no longer contained chlorine that could deplete the ozone layer.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] R-134a is a greenhouse gas, it has a lower global warming potential than R-12.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] New cars produced in the early 1990s contained the new refrigerant in their air conditioning systems.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Owners of older cars with R-12 systems would either have to invest in an R-12 to R-134a conversion system, buy a new car, or find a qualified technician to recharge their older R-12 system.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] R-134a has been used in cars for almost 30 years.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] R-134a’s global warming potential number is about 1,430.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The third and newest automotive air conditioning refrigerant is R-1234yf.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] R-1234yf is a hydrofluoroolefin refrigerant that contains hydrogen, fluorine, and also carbon elements.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The refrigerant was developed by the DuPont/Honeywell company and is more expensive per pound than R-134a.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] R-1234yf can be found in late-model cars and is not cross-compatible with older R-134a or R-12 systems.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Of the three refrigerants, R-1234yf is the best for the environment with the lowest global warming potential number which is about a three.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] In the refrigeration cycle, heat is transported from the cabin to the environment similar to a refrigerator that transports heat from the interior and into the ambient environment.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The hot, compressed refrigerant vapor is now at a temperature and pressure at which it can be condensed and is routed through a condenser, usually in front of the car's radiator to be the first heat rejection component and to take advantage of the car’s velocities when traveling.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Thus, the circulating refrigerant ejects heat from the cab interior and the heat is carried away into the environment by the air flowing across the condenser.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] That pressure reduction results in flash evaporation of a part of the liquid refrigerant, lowering its temperature.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The cold refrigerant is then routed through the evaporator coil in the passenger compartment.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] When the expansion device is a simple fixed metering orifice, known as an orifice tube, the receiver-drier is instead located between the evaporator outlet and the compressor, and in this case, it is known as an accumulator.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] In such an air conditioning system, the accumulator also prevents the liquid refrigerant from reaching the compressor during low cooling demand periods.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The air, often after being filtered by a cabin air filter, is blown by an adjustable speed electric powered centrifugal fan across the evaporator, causing the liquid part of the cold refrigerant mixture to evaporate as well, further lowering the temperature.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The warm air is therefore cooled, and also deprived of any humidity (which condenses on the evaporator coils and is drained outside of the vehicle) in the process.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] It is then passed through a heater matrix, inside of which the engine's coolant circulates, where it can be reheated to a certain degree or even a certain temperature selected by the user and then delivered inside the vehicle's cabin through a set of adjustable vents.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Another way of adjusting the desired air temperature, this time by working on the system's cooling capacity, is precisely regulating the centrifugal fan speed so that only the strictly required volumetric flow rate of air is cooled by the evaporator.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The user is also given the option to close the vehicle's external air flaps, to achieve even faster and stronger cooling by recirculating the already-cooled air inside the cabin to the evaporator.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Finally, whenever the compressor can be commanded to operate in a reduced displacement, the vent temperature can also be controlled by acting upon the compressor's displacement.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Evaporator freeze over, which stops air from flowing through the evaporator fins, can be prevented in different ways.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] A temperature switch or a thermistor can control the evaporator coil surface temperature, and a pressure switch or sensing element can monitor the suction pressure (which is in relationship with the refrigerant's evaporating temperature).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] To complete the refrigeration cycle, the refrigerant vapor is routed back into the compressor.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The warmer the air that reaches the evaporator, the higher the pressure of the vapor mixture discharged from it and therefore the higher the load placed on the compressor and therefore on the engine to keep the refrigerant flowing through the system.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Compressor load is also proportional to the condensing temperature.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] There are different methods for the repair and maintenance of the tube connections ensuring the refrigeration cycle.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Conventional methods like soldering or welding lead to time and damaging soiling issues.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The Lokring connection which is based on compressed fittings is easy to use and thus more time-efficient.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Air conditioning systems in cars require special maintenance.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Normally the lifetime losses of refrigerant are small and have no effect.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] But the system should be checked for any loss in a two to four year circle; at least, when the cooling capacity decreases.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Biogrowth in air conditioning systems can be reduced for a limited time only.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Hygiene measures should be applied regularly.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The Standard 6032 of the Association of German Engineers (VDI) provides an overview of the hygienic maintenance of vehicle air conditioning systems according to the state of the art.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] A regular, professional hygiene check of a vehicle's air conditioning system includes checking the drain lines for the condensation water, annual cleaning of the air conditioning system evaporator and changing the interior air filter (pollen filter).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] In particular, the unhindered drainage of the condensation water from the air conditioning system evaporator must be ensured, otherwise the moisture will remain within the system and uncontrolled nests for biological colonization will arise.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Due to the physical framework conditions, the forced separation of condensed water, air conditioning evaporators in motor vehicles have a very important health and hygiene function.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Regular cleaning of the air conditioning evaporator must therefore ensure that the biological colonization of the surface is interrupted and that the sometimes toxic decay products of bacteria (endotoxins) or metabolites of mold (mycotoxins) are safely removed from the lamella system.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The necessity of hygienic cleaning of ventilation systems in vehicles at regular intervals is not only logically understandable, but is also described by the technical guideline and standard VDI 6032 of the Association of German Engineers.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Particles such as Dust, (animal) hair and/or fungal growth, dander, etc. and remain on the pollen filter shaft and the surrounding walls.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The air conditioner quickly becomes a dirt and germ spinner.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Merely replacing the air filter of an HVAC system as part of the inspection is not enough.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The pollen filter box must be cleaned professionally and the air conditioning system evaporator must be flushed hygienically and effectively with cleaners without fragrances (allergy triggers) every 24 months at the latest.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] With a professional air conditioning system cleaning according to the current state of the art, mould, germs, bacteria and other odor-forming substances or deposits are literally washed away at the point of origin.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] This is the only way to ensure the required indoor air hygiene in the vehicle.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The choice of approved cleaning agents and methods is also crucial here.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] These were also clearly described by the VDI in the 6032 standard for cleaning air conditioning systems.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] With this method, the air conditioning evaporator is completely flushed with a cleaning liquid introduced through a probe.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The evaporator is then as clean as a new component and completely free of deposits or substances that form a culture medium.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Only the combination of mechanical cleaning and a cleaning agent ensures working results.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Meanwhile, both the driver and all passengers are exposed to an invisible health risk.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Air filters that are not replaced regularly (once or twice a year) often look as shown and are a source of germs, especially for mould.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Pollen decompose in the filter within 12 weeks.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] This decomposition process releases its actual allergen.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] These have a particle size that cannot be retained by the pollen filter.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The air flow through the pollen filter leads to an increasingly poor air quality inside the vehicle.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Especially in overloaded filters that have been used for a long time, particle sizes develop that are below the filter performance.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The particles of microorganisms, pollen, germs and bacteria are released directly to the moist surface environment of the air conditioning system evaporator via the clean air side of the filter.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Therefore, the air conditioning evaporator should also be professionally cleaned once a year.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The same applies to an air conditioning evaporator that is not professionally cleaned regularly.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Bacteria also settle on its surface and lead to an ever increasing biogrowth due to the continuous moisture of the component.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Hygienic problems also arise if the evaporator is cleaned incorrectly or treated with unsuitable cleaning agents.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Cleaning agents that are too harsh destroy or damage the protective coating of the fin evaporator structure.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] This can change the drip angle of the condensate and increases the discharge volume on the evaporator.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The result is misdirected, bacterially contaminated condensate that accumulates in unexpected places within the air conditioning system.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The vehicle owner must personally ensure that the workshop carries out a hygienic cleaning of the air conditioning system using a chemical-mechanical process recommended by the VDI as part of the inspection or an upcoming air filter change.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Since the method described has not yet become established in everyday workshop practice, the use of so-called "one click cans" is currently enjoying great popularity.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Not only because they are printed with the addition "air conditioning cleaner".
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Most of the contents of these cans are randomly distributed in the vehicle and settle there.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The part that could actually be sucked in by the ventilation system via the circulating air ends up on the cabin air filter.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Nothing gets on the vaporizer with this method.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Only scents and aromas are distributed in the vehicle with the click cans.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Only the combination of mechanical pressure flushing and a suitable cleaning agent directly on the evaporator leads to the desired result.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Although air conditioners use significant power, the drag of a car with closed windows is less than if the windows are open to cool the occupants.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] There has been much debate on the effect of installing air conditioning and its effect during use on the fuel efficiency of a vehicle.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Other factors can affect the engine, and an overall engine heat increase can affect the cooling system of the vehicle.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] In a modern automobile, the A/C system will use around 4 horsepower (3.0 kW) of the engine's power to reject the target calculated heat loading of the cabin, thus increasing fuel consumption of the vehicle.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Sustainable automotive air conditioning is the subject of a debate – also known as the *Cool War* – about the next-generation refrigerant in car air conditioning.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] An advocacy group, *The Alliance for CO2 Solutions*, supports the uptake of carbon dioxide (CO2) as a refrigerant in passenger cars, and the chemical industry is developing new chemical blends.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The Alliance for CO2 Solutions propositions the car industry to replace more unsustainable chemical substances with the natural refrigerant like carbon dioxide (CO2, R744/ R-744) in car cooling and heating.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] They claim that this would lead to 10% fewer emissions from new cars, potentially reducing global greenhouse gas emissions by 1%.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Opponents of the advocacy group claim that CO2 refrigeration technology is not cost-efficient nor safe, and support the development of new chemical refrigerant blends instead.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] A debate had emanated from the decision of the European Union to phase out the current high global warming refrigerant HFC-134a in car air conditioning from January 2011 onwards.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] To comply with the legislation carmakers have to decide on new refrigerants, as they typically need 3 to 4 years to develop and introduce a new car platform including the new air conditioning system.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] CO2 Technology requires the design of completely new high-pressure systems whereas so-called "drop-in solutions" (the adaptation of current systems to new substances) are potentially more cost-efficient.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The Alliance for CO2 Solutions claims, however that the initial costs of CO2 systems will be around €5 higher than drop-in solutions and that over a car's life cycle, CO2 air conditioning systems will be more cost-efficient than any currently used or proposed new chemical blends.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] CO2 has been classified as Safety Class A1 (low-toxic, non-flammable refrigerant) by the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE) – the highest safety class possible.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] As the charge of CO2 to the air conditioning systems is very small (200-400 g) there is no real danger for the passengers, even in case of accidental release.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Butane and propane are very flammable petroleum products; they are used as fuels for gas barbecue grills, disposable lighters, etc.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Like gasoline, to which it chemically is closely related, propane tends to explode if mixed with oxygen and ignited in an enclosed container.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] The use of highly flammable hydrocarbon gases such as butane and propane as automotive refrigerants raises serious safety concerns.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] All of the refrigerants which the EPA approved for motor vehicle use in place of CFC-12 (as of 28 September 2006) contain no more than 4% of total flammable hydrocarbons (butane, isobutane, and/or isopentane).
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Therefore, it appears unlikely, for safety reasons, that EPA will approve 'Greenfreeze' or similar hydrocarbon-based refrigerants for automotive use.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] In September 2007, the German Association of the Automotive Industry (VDA) officially announced its decision to use CO2 as the refrigerant in next-generation air conditioning.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] A working group at the European Automobile Manufacturers Association (ACEA) proposed drafting an industry-wide common position.
[src:automobile-engine-replacement/automotive-air-conditioning] Reports later claimed VDA members would avoid complying with the EU directive through legal loopholes.
